	<div id="content">
		<a name="top" id="top"></a>
		<div id="siteNotice"><script type='text/javascript'>if (wgNotice != '') document.writeln(wgNotice);</script></div>		<h1 id="firstHeading" class="firstHeading">Glossary of wine terms</h1>
		<div id="bodyContent">
			<h3 id="siteSub">From Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia</h3>
			<div id="contentSub"></div>
									<div id="jump-to-nav">Jump to: <a href="#column-one">navigation</a>, <a href="#searchInput">search</a></div>			<!-- start content -->
			<p>The <b>glossary of wine terms</b> lists the definitions of many general terms used within the wine industry. For terms specific to <a href="/wiki/Viticulture" title="Viticulture">viticulture</a>, <a href="/wiki/Winemaking" title="Winemaking">winemaking</a>, grape varieties, and <a href="/wiki/Wine_tasting" title="Wine tasting">wine tasting</a>, see the topic specific list in the "<i><a href="/wiki/Glossary_of_wine_terms#See_also" title="Glossary of wine terms">See Also</a></i>" section below.</p>
<p><b>Contents:</b> <a href="#top" title="">Top</a> - <a href="#0.E2.80.939" title="">0â€“9</a> <a href="#A" title="">A</a> <a href="#B" title="">B</a> <a href="#C" title="">C</a> <a href="#D" title="">D</a> <a href="#E" title="">E</a> <a href="#F" title="">F</a> <a href="#G" title="">G</a> <a href="#H" title="">H</a> <a href="#I" title="">I</a> <a href="#J" title="">J</a> <a href="#K" title="">K</a> <a href="#L" title="">L</a> <a href="#M" title="">M</a> <a href="#N" title="">N</a> <a href="#O" title="">O</a> <a href="#P" title="">P</a> <a href="#Q" title="">Q</a> <a href="#R" title="">R</a> <a href="#S" title="">S</a> <a href="#T" title="">T</a> <a href="#U" title="">U</a> <a href="#V" title="">V</a> <a href="#W" title="">W</a> <a href="#X" title="">X</a> <a href="#Y" title="">Y</a> <a href="#Z" title="">Z</a></p>
<p><a name="A" id="A"></a></p>
<h2><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Glossary_of_wine_terms&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1" title="Edit section: A">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline">A</span></h2>
<p><a name="A.B.C." id="A.B.C."></a></p>
<h5><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Glossary_of_wine_terms&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2" title="Edit section: A.B.C.">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline">A.B.C.</span></h5>
<dl>
<dd><a href="/wiki/Acronym" title="Acronym" class="mw-redirect">Acronym</a> for "Anything but <a href="/wiki/Chardonnay" title="Chardonnay">Chardonnay</a>" or "Anything but <a href="/wiki/Cabernet" title="Cabernet" class="mw-redirect">Cabernet</a>". A term conceived by <a href="/wiki/Bonny_Doon_(wine)" title="Bonny Doon (wine)" class="mw-redirect">Bonny Doon</a>'s <a href="/w/index.php?title=Randall_Grahm&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1" class="new" title="Randall Grahm (page does not exist)">Randall Grahm</a> to describe wine drinkers interest in <a href="/wiki/Grape_varieties" title="Grape varieties" class="mw-redirect">grape varieties</a> beyond the widely planted Chardonnay and Cabernet.<sup id="cite_ref-Stevenson_pg_629_0-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Stevenson_pg_629-0" title=""><span>[</span>1<span>]</span></a></sup></dd>
</dl>
<p><a name="A.B.V." id="A.B.V."></a></p>
<h5><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Glossary_of_wine_terms&amp;action=edit&amp;section=3" title="Edit section: A.B.V.">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline">A.B.V.</span></h5>
<dl>
<dd>Abbreviation of <a href="/wiki/Alcohol_by_volume" title="Alcohol by volume">alcohol by volume</a>, generally listed on a <a href="/wiki/Wine_label" title="Wine label">wine label</a>.</dd>
</dl>
<p><a name="AC" id="AC"></a></p>
<h5><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Glossary_of_wine_terms&amp;action=edit&amp;section=4" title="Edit section: AC">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline">AC</span></h5>
<dl>
<dd>Abbreviation for "Agricultural <a href="/wiki/Cooperative" title="Cooperative">Cooperative</a>" on <a href="/wiki/Greek_wine" title="Greek wine">Greek wine</a> labels and for <i>Adega Cooperativa</i> on <a href="/wiki/Portuguese_(wine)" title="Portuguese (wine)" class="mw-redirect">Portuguese</a> labels.</dd>
</dl>
<p><a name="Adega" id="Adega"></a></p>
<h5><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Glossary_of_wine_terms&amp;action=edit&amp;section=5" title="Edit section: Adega">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline">Adega</span></h5>
<dl>
<dd>Portuguese wine term for a winery or wine cellar.</dd>
</dl>
<p><a name="Altar_wine" id="Altar_wine"></a></p>
<h5><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Glossary_of_wine_terms&amp;action=edit&amp;section=6" title="Edit section: Altar wine">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline"><a href="/wiki/Altar_wine" title="Altar wine" class="mw-redirect">Altar wine</a></span></h5>
<dl>
<dd>The wine used by the <a href="/wiki/Catholic_Church" title="Catholic Church" class="mw-redirect">Catholic Church</a> in celebrations of the <a href="/wiki/Eucharist" title="Eucharist">Eucharist</a>.</dd>
</dl>
<p><a name="A.O.C." id="A.O.C."></a></p>
<h5><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Glossary_of_wine_terms&amp;action=edit&amp;section=7" title="Edit section: A.O.C.">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline">A.O.C.</span></h5>
<dl>
<dd>Abbreviation for <a href="/wiki/Appellation_d%27Origine_Contr%C3%B4l%C3%A9e" title="Appellation d'Origine ContrÃ´lÃ©e" class="mw-redirect">Appellation d'Origine ContrÃ´lÃ©e</a>, (<a href="/wiki/English_language" title="English language">English</a>: <span lang="en" xml:lang="en"><i><a href="/wiki/Appellation" title="Appellation">Appellation</a> of controlled origin</i></span>), as specified under <a href="/wiki/France" title="France">French</a> law. The AOC laws specify and delimit the geography from which a particular wine (or other food product) may originate and methods by which it may be made. The regulations are administered by the <i><a href="/wiki/Institut_National_des_Appellations_d%27Origine" title="Institut National des Appellations d'Origine">Institut National des Appellations d'Origine</a></i> (INAO).</dd>
</dl>
<p><a name="A.P._number" id="A.P._number"></a></p>
<h5><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Glossary_of_wine_terms&amp;action=edit&amp;section=8" title="Edit section: A.P. number">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline">A.P. number</span></h5>
<dl>
<dd>Abbreviation for <i><b>Amtliche PrÃ¼fungsnummer</b></i>, the official testing number displayed on a <a href="/wiki/German_wine_label" title="German wine label">German wine label</a> that shows that the wine was tasted and passed government <a href="/wiki/Quality_control" title="Quality control">quality control</a> standards.</dd>
</dl>
<p><a name="ATTTB" id="ATTTB"></a></p>
<h5><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Glossary_of_wine_terms&amp;action=edit&amp;section=9" title="Edit section: ATTTB">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline"><a href="/wiki/Alcohol_and_Tobacco_Tax_and_Trade_Bureau" title="Alcohol and Tobacco Tax and Trade Bureau">ATTTB</a></span></h5>
<dl>
<dd>Abbreviation for the Alcohol and Tobacco Tax and Trade Bureau, a United States government agency which is primarily responsible for the regulation of wines sold and produced in the United States.</dd>
</dl>
<p><a name="Anbaugebiet" id="Anbaugebiet"></a></p>
<h5><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Glossary_of_wine_terms&amp;action=edit&amp;section=10" title="Edit section: Anbaugebiet">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline">Anbaugebiet</span></h5>
<dl>
<dd>A <a href="/wiki/German_wine" title="German wine">German wine</a> region. Anbaugebiet are further divided into <i>bereiche</i> or districts.</dd>
</dl>
<p><a name="Aperitif" id="Aperitif"></a></p>
<h5><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Glossary_of_wine_terms&amp;action=edit&amp;section=11" title="Edit section: Aperitif">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline"><a href="/wiki/Aperitif" title="Aperitif" class="mw-redirect">Aperitif</a></span></h5>
<dl>
<dd>A wine that is either drunk by itself (i.e. without food) or before a meal in order to stimulate the appetite.</dd>
</dl>
<p><a name="Appellation" id="Appellation"></a></p>
<h5><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Glossary_of_wine_terms&amp;action=edit&amp;section=12" title="Edit section: Appellation">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline"><a href="/wiki/Appellation" title="Appellation">Appellation</a></span></h5>
<dl>
<dd>A geographically delineated wine region.</dd>
</dl>
<p><a name="Ausbruch" id="Ausbruch"></a></p>
<h5><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Glossary_of_wine_terms&amp;action=edit&amp;section=13" title="Edit section: Ausbruch">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline"><a href="/wiki/Ausbruch" title="Ausbruch">Ausbruch</a></span></h5>
<dl>
<dd>Austrian term originally referring to the <i><a href="/wiki/Asz%C3%BA" title="AszÃº" class="mw-redirect">aszÃº</a></i> production method of mixing grapes affected by <a href="/wiki/Noble_rot" title="Noble rot">noble rot</a> with a fermenting base wine. Today a <a href="/wiki/Pr%C3%A4dikat" title="PrÃ¤dikat" class="mw-redirect">PrÃ¤dikat</a> in Austria, intermediate between <a href="/wiki/Beerenauslese" title="Beerenauslese">Beerenauslese</a> and <a href="/wiki/Trockenbeerenauslese" title="Trockenbeerenauslese">Trockenbeerenauslese</a>.</dd>
</dl>
<p><a name="Auslese" id="Auslese"></a></p>
<h5><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Glossary_of_wine_terms&amp;action=edit&amp;section=14" title="Edit section: Auslese">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline"><a href="/wiki/Auslese" title="Auslese">Auslese</a></span></h5>
<dl>
<dd>German for "select harvest", a <a href="/wiki/Pr%C3%A4dikat" title="PrÃ¤dikat" class="mw-redirect">PrÃ¤dikat</a> in Germany and Austria.</dd>
</dl>
<p><a name="B" id="B"></a></p>
<h2><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Glossary_of_wine_terms&amp;action=edit&amp;section=15" title="Edit section: B">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline">B</span></h2>
<div class="thumb tright">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:202px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Lightmatter_wine_barrels.jpg" class="image" title="Barrels"><img alt="" src="http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/66/Lightmatter_wine_barrels.jpg/200px-Lightmatter_wine_barrels.jpg" width="200" height="133" border="0" class="thumbimage" /></a>
<div class="thumbcaption">
<div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:Lightmatter_wine_barrels.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"><img src="/skins-1.5/common/images/magnify-clip.png" width="15" height="11" alt="" /></a></div>
Barrels</div>
</div>
</div>
<p><a name="Balthazar" id="Balthazar"></a></p>
<h5><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Glossary_of_wine_terms&amp;action=edit&amp;section=16" title="Edit section: Balthazar">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline">Balthazar</span></h5>
<dl>
<dd>A large bottle containing 12 <a href="/wiki/Litre" title="Litre">litres</a>, the equivalent of 16 regular <a href="/wiki/Wine_bottle" title="Wine bottle">wine bottles</a>.</dd>
</dl>
<p><a name="Ban_de_Vendage" id="Ban_de_Vendage"></a></p>
<h5><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Glossary_of_wine_terms&amp;action=edit&amp;section=17" title="Edit section: Ban de Vendage">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline">Ban de Vendage</span></h5>
<dl>
<dd>The official start of the harvest season in France.</dd>
</dl>
<p><a name="Barrique" id="Barrique"></a></p>
<h5><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Glossary_of_wine_terms&amp;action=edit&amp;section=18" title="Edit section: Barrique">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline"><a href="/wiki/Barrique" title="Barrique" class="mw-redirect">Barrique</a></span></h5>
<dl>
<dd>The French name for a 225 litre <a href="/wiki/Bordeaux" title="Bordeaux">Bordeaux</a> style barrel (Bordeaux <a href="/wiki/Hogshead" title="Hogshead">hogshead</a>). Will yield 24 cases of 12 bottles each.<sup id="cite_ref-ALE-bar_1-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-ALE-bar-1" title=""><span>[</span>2<span>]</span></a></sup></dd>
</dl>
<p><a name="Basic" id="Basic"></a></p>
<h5><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Glossary_of_wine_terms&amp;action=edit&amp;section=19" title="Edit section: Basic">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline">Basic</span></h5>
<dl>
<dd>A low cost entry level offering from a winery as opposed to its more expensive <b>premium</b> wine offerings.</dd>
</dl>
<p><a name="Beerenauslese" id="Beerenauslese"></a></p>
<h5><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Glossary_of_wine_terms&amp;action=edit&amp;section=20" title="Edit section: Beerenauslese">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline"><a href="/wiki/Beerenauslese" title="Beerenauslese">Beerenauslese</a></span></h5>
<dl>
<dd>A German term meaning approximately "harvest of selected berries". A <a href="/wiki/Pr%C3%A4dikat" title="PrÃ¤dikat" class="mw-redirect">PrÃ¤dikat</a> in Germany and Austria.</dd>
</dl>
<p><a name="Bereich" id="Bereich"></a></p>
<h5><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Glossary_of_wine_terms&amp;action=edit&amp;section=21" title="Edit section: Bereich">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline">Bereich</span></h5>
<dl>
<dd>A district within a German wine region <i>(Anbaugebiet)</i>. Contains smaller <i>Grosslagen</i> vineyard designations.</dd>
</dl>
<p><a name="The_Berthomeau_Report" id="The_Berthomeau_Report"></a></p>
<h5><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Glossary_of_wine_terms&amp;action=edit&amp;section=22" title="Edit section: The Berthomeau Report">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline"><a href="/wiki/The_Berthomeau_Report" title="The Berthomeau Report" class="mw-redirect">The Berthomeau Report</a></span></h5>
<dl>
<dd>Commissioned by French Ministry of Agriculture to better position the wine industry for the future.</dd>
</dl>
<p><a name="Blind_tasting" id="Blind_tasting"></a></p>
<h5><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Glossary_of_wine_terms&amp;action=edit&amp;section=23" title="Edit section: Blind tasting">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline"><a href="/wiki/Blind_tasting_of_wine" title="Blind tasting of wine" class="mw-redirect">Blind tasting</a></span></h5>
<dl>
<dd><a href="/wiki/Wine_tasting" title="Wine tasting">Tasting</a> and evaluating wine without knowing what it is.</dd>
</dl>
<p><a name="B.O.B." id="B.O.B."></a></p>
<h5><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Glossary_of_wine_terms&amp;action=edit&amp;section=24" title="Edit section: B.O.B.">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline">B.O.B.</span></h5>
<dl>
<dd>An acronym for "Buyer's Own Brand" which refers to a <a href="/wiki/Private_label" title="Private label">private label</a> wine owned by the restaurant or retailer that sells the wine.</dd>
</dl>
<p><a name="Bodega" id="Bodega"></a></p>
<h5><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Glossary_of_wine_terms&amp;action=edit&amp;section=25" title="Edit section: Bodega">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline"><a href="/wiki/Bodega" title="Bodega">Bodega</a></span></h5>
<dl>
<dd>A Spanish <a href="/wiki/Wine_cellar" title="Wine cellar">wine cellar</a>. Also refers to a seller of alcoholic beverage.</dd>
</dl>
<div class="thumb tright">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:152px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Empty_Wine_bottle.jpg" class="image" title="An empty wine bottle."><img alt="" src="http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/16/Empty_Wine_bottle.jpg/150px-Empty_Wine_bottle.jpg" width="150" height="220" border="0" class="thumbimage" /></a>
<div class="thumbcaption">
<div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:Empty_Wine_bottle.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"><img src="/skins-1.5/common/images/magnify-clip.png" width="15" height="11" alt="" /></a></div>
<small>An empty wine bottle.</small></div>
</div>
</div>
<p><a name="Bota" id="Bota"></a></p>
<h5><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Glossary_of_wine_terms&amp;action=edit&amp;section=26" title="Edit section: Bota">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline">Bota</span></h5>
<dl>
<dd>A cask of wine used to store <a href="/wiki/Sherry" title="Sherry">Sherry</a> with a capacity between 159 to 172 <a href="/wiki/Gallon" title="Gallon">gallons</a> (600-650 <a href="/wiki/Liter" title="Liter" class="mw-redirect">liters</a>)</dd>
</dl>
<p><a name="Bottle" id="Bottle"></a></p>
<h5><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Glossary_of_wine_terms&amp;action=edit&amp;section=27" title="Edit section: Bottle">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline"><a href="/wiki/Bottle" title="Bottle">Bottle</a></span></h5>
<dl>
<dd>A bottle is a small container with a neck that is narrower than the body and a "mouth." Modern wine bottles are nearly always made of glass because it is nonporous, strong, and aesthetically pleasing.</dd>
</dl>
<p><a name="Breathing" id="Breathing"></a></p>
<h5><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Glossary_of_wine_terms&amp;action=edit&amp;section=28" title="Edit section: Breathing">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline"><a href="/wiki/Breathing_(wine)" title="Breathing (wine)" class="mw-redirect">Breathing</a></span></h5>
<dl>
<dd>The interaction between air and wine after a wine has been opened. Breathing may take place while the wine is <a href="/wiki/Decanting_(wine)" title="Decanting (wine)" class="mw-redirect">decanting</a>.</dd>
</dl>
<p><a name="C" id="C"></a></p>
<h2><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Glossary_of_wine_terms&amp;action=edit&amp;section=29" title="Edit section: C">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline">C</span></h2>
<p><a name="C.A." id="C.A."></a></p>
<h5><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Glossary_of_wine_terms&amp;action=edit&amp;section=30" title="Edit section: C.A.">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline">C.A.</span></h5>
<dl>
<dd>Abbreviation seen on <a href="/wiki/Spanish_(wine)" title="Spanish (wine)" class="mw-redirect">Spanish</a> <a href="/wiki/Wine_labels" title="Wine labels" class="mw-redirect">wine labels</a> meaning <i>Cooperativa AgrÃ­cola</i> or local <a href="/wiki/Co-operative" title="Co-operative" class="mw-redirect">co-operative</a>.</dd>
</dl>
<p><a name="California_cult_wines" id="California_cult_wines"></a></p>
<h5><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Glossary_of_wine_terms&amp;action=edit&amp;section=31" title="Edit section: California cult wines">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline"><a href="/wiki/California_cult_wines" title="California cult wines" class="mw-redirect">California cult wines</a></span></h5>
<dl>
<dd>Certain California wines for which consumers and others pay higher prices than those of Bordeaux's First Growths (Premiers Crus).</dd>
</dl>
<p><a name="Cantina" id="Cantina"></a></p>
<h5><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Glossary_of_wine_terms&amp;action=edit&amp;section=32" title="Edit section: Cantina">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline">Cantina</span></h5>
<dl>
<dd><a href="/wiki/Italian_(wine)" title="Italian (wine)" class="mw-redirect">Italian</a> term for winery.</dd>
</dl>
<p><a name="Cantina_Sociale" id="Cantina_Sociale"></a></p>
<h5><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Glossary_of_wine_terms&amp;action=edit&amp;section=33" title="Edit section: Cantina Sociale">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline">Cantina Sociale</span></h5>
<dl>
<dd>Italian term for a co-ooperative</dd>
</dl>
<p><a name="Capsule" id="Capsule"></a></p>
<h5><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Glossary_of_wine_terms&amp;action=edit&amp;section=34" title="Edit section: Capsule">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline">Capsule</span></h5>
<dl>
<dd>The plastic or foil that covers the <a href="/wiki/Cork_(material)" title="Cork (material)">cork</a> and part of the neck of a <a href="/wiki/Wine_bottle" title="Wine bottle">wine bottle</a>.</dd>
</dl>
<p><a name="Cellar_door" id="Cellar_door"></a></p>
<h5><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Glossary_of_wine_terms&amp;action=edit&amp;section=35" title="Edit section: Cellar door">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline">Cellar door</span></h5>
<dl>
<dd>The area of the winery where <a href="/wiki/Point_of_sale" title="Point of sale">point of sale</a> purchases occur. This can be a tasting room or a separate sales area.</dd>
</dl>
<p><a name="C.C3.A9page" id="C.C3.A9page"></a></p>
<h5><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Glossary_of_wine_terms&amp;action=edit&amp;section=36" title="Edit section: CÃ©page">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline">CÃ©page</span></h5>
<dl>
<dd>French term for <a href="/wiki/Grape_variety" title="Grape variety" class="mw-redirect">grape variety</a>. When it appears on a wine label it will usually refer to the <a href="/wiki/Varietal" title="Varietal">varietals</a> used to make the wine.</dd>
</dl>
<p><a name="Chai" id="Chai"></a></p>
<h5><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Glossary_of_wine_terms&amp;action=edit&amp;section=37" title="Edit section: Chai">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline">Chai</span></h5>
<dl>
<dd>A wine shed, or other storage place above ground, used for storing <a href="/wiki/Glossary_of_wine_terms#Barrel" title="Glossary of wine terms">casks</a>, common in Bordeaux. Usually different types of wine are kept in separate sheds.<sup id="cite_ref-ALE_2-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-ALE-2" title=""><span>[</span>3<span>]</span></a></sup> The person in charge of vinification and ageing of all wine made at an estate, or the <i>chais</i> of a <i><a href="/wiki/Glossary_of_wine_terms#N.C3.A9gociant" title="Glossary of wine terms">nÃ©gociant</a></i>, is titled a <i>MaÃ®tre de Chai</i>.<sup id="cite_ref-ALEmdc_3-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-ALEmdc-3" title=""><span>[</span>4<span>]</span></a></sup> The New World counterpart to the chai may be called the barrel hall.<sup id="cite_ref-OCW-chai_4-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-OCW-chai-4" title=""><span>[</span>5<span>]</span></a></sup></dd>
</dl>
<p><a name="Champagne_flute" id="Champagne_flute"></a></p>
<h5><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Glossary_of_wine_terms&amp;action=edit&amp;section=38" title="Edit section: Champagne flute">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline"><a href="/wiki/Champagne_flute" title="Champagne flute" class="mw-redirect">Champagne flute</a></span></h5>
<dl>
<dd>A piece of <a href="/wiki/Stemware" title="Stemware">stemware</a> having a long stem with a tall, narrow bowl on top.</dd>
</dl>
<p><a name="Ch.C3.A2teau" id="Ch.C3.A2teau"></a></p>
<h5><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Glossary_of_wine_terms&amp;action=edit&amp;section=39" title="Edit section: ChÃ¢teau">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline"><a href="/wiki/Ch%C3%A2teau" title="ChÃ¢teau">ChÃ¢teau</a></span></h5>
<dl>
<dd>Generally a <a href="/wiki/Winery" title="Winery">winery</a> in <a href="/wiki/Bordeaux" title="Bordeaux">Bordeaux</a>, although the term is sometimes used for wineries in other parts of the world, such as the <a href="/wiki/List_of_wineries_in_the_Barossa_Valley" title="List of wineries in the Barossa Valley">Barossa Valley</a>.</dd>
</dl>
<p><a name="Clairet" id="Clairet"></a></p>
<h5><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Glossary_of_wine_terms&amp;action=edit&amp;section=40" title="Edit section: Clairet">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline"><a href="/wiki/Clairet" title="Clairet">Clairet</a></span></h5>
<dl>
<dd>A French term for a wine that falls between the range of a light red wine and a dark <a href="/wiki/Ros%C3%A9" title="RosÃ©">rosÃ©</a></dd>
</dl>
<p><a name="Claret" id="Claret"></a></p>
<h5><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Glossary_of_wine_terms&amp;action=edit&amp;section=41" title="Edit section: Claret">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline"><a href="/wiki/Claret" title="Claret">Claret</a></span></h5>
<dl>
<dd><a href="/wiki/British_English" title="British English">British</a> name for <a href="/wiki/Bordeaux_wine" title="Bordeaux wine">Bordeaux wine</a>. Is also a <a href="/wiki/Semi-generic" title="Semi-generic">semi-generic</a> term for a red wine in similar style to that of <a href="/wiki/Bordeaux_wine" title="Bordeaux wine">Bordeaux</a>.</dd>
</dl>
<p><a name="Classico" id="Classico"></a></p>
<h5><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Glossary_of_wine_terms&amp;action=edit&amp;section=42" title="Edit section: Classico">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline">Classico</span></h5>
<dl>
<dd>An Italian term for the historical or "classic" center of a wine region--sometimes located in the heart of a DOC.</dd>
</dl>
<p><a name="Cleanskin" id="Cleanskin"></a></p>
<h5><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Glossary_of_wine_terms&amp;action=edit&amp;section=43" title="Edit section: Cleanskin">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline"><a href="/wiki/Cleanskin_(wine)" title="Cleanskin (wine)">Cleanskin</a></span></h5>
<dl>
<dd>In Australia, wine bottled without a commercial label, usually sold cheaply in bulk quantities.</dd>
</dl>
<p><a name="Climat" id="Climat"></a></p>
<h5><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Glossary_of_wine_terms&amp;action=edit&amp;section=44" title="Edit section: Climat">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline">Climat</span></h5>
<dl>
<dd>French term for a single plot of land located within a vineyard that has its own name and demonstrated <i><a href="/wiki/Terroir" title="Terroir">terroir</a></i>.</dd>
</dl>
<p><a name="Coates_Law_of_Maturity" id="Coates_Law_of_Maturity"></a></p>
<h5><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Glossary_of_wine_terms&amp;action=edit&amp;section=45" title="Edit section: Coates Law of Maturity">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline"><a href="/wiki/Coates_Law_of_Maturity" title="Coates Law of Maturity">Coates Law of Maturity</a></span></h5>
<dl>
<dd>A principle relating to the <a href="/wiki/Aging_ability_(wine)" title="Aging ability (wine)" class="mw-redirect">aging ability</a> of wine that states that a wine will remain at its peak (or optimal) drinking quality for as long as it took to reach the point of maturity that it already was at. For example, if a wine is drinking at its peak at 1 year of age, it will continue drinking at its peak for another year.</dd>
</dl>
<p><a name="Commercial_wine" id="Commercial_wine"></a></p>
<h5><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Glossary_of_wine_terms&amp;action=edit&amp;section=46" title="Edit section: Commercial wine">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline">Commercial wine</span></h5>
<dl>
<dd>A mass produce wine aimed for the wide market of wine drinkers made according to a set formula, year after year. These wines tend to emphasis broad appeal and easy drink-ability rather than <i>terroir</i> or craftsmanship.</dd>
</dl>
<p><a name="Corkscrew" id="Corkscrew"></a></p>
<h5><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Glossary_of_wine_terms&amp;action=edit&amp;section=47" title="Edit section: Corkscrew">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline"><a href="/wiki/Corkscrew_(tool)" title="Corkscrew (tool)" class="mw-redirect">Corkscrew</a></span></h5>
<dl>
<dd>A tool, comprising a pointed metallic <a href="/wiki/Helix" title="Helix">helix</a> attached to a handle, for drawing <a href="/wiki/Cork_(material)" title="Cork (material)">Corks</a> from bottles.</dd>
</dl>
<p><a name="C.C3.B4tes" id="C.C3.B4tes"></a></p>
<h5><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Glossary_of_wine_terms&amp;action=edit&amp;section=48" title="Edit section: CÃ´tes">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline">CÃ´tes</span></h5>
<dl>
<dd>French term for the hillside or slopes of one contiguous hill region.</dd>
</dl>
<p><a name="Coteaux" id="Coteaux"></a></p>
<h5><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Glossary_of_wine_terms&amp;action=edit&amp;section=49" title="Edit section: Coteaux">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline">Coteaux</span></h5>
<dl>
<dd>French term for the hillside or slopes of a hill region that is not contiguous.</dd>
</dl>
<p><a name="Country_wine" id="Country_wine"></a></p>
<h5><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Glossary_of_wine_terms&amp;action=edit&amp;section=50" title="Edit section: Country wine">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline"><a href="/wiki/Country_wine" title="Country wine">Country wine</a></span></h5>
<dl>
<dd>A quality level intermediate between <a href="/wiki/Table_wine" title="Table wine">table wine</a> and <a href="/wiki/Quality_wine" title="Quality wine" class="mw-redirect">quality wine</a>, which in France is known as <i><a href="/wiki/Vin_de_pays" title="Vin de pays">vin de pays</a></i>. Also a synonym for <a href="#Fruit_wine" title="">Fruit wine</a>.</dd>
</dl>
<p><a name="Cr.C3.A9mant" id="Cr.C3.A9mant"></a></p>
<h5><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Glossary_of_wine_terms&amp;action=edit&amp;section=51" title="Edit section: CrÃ©mant">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline"><a href="/wiki/Cr%C3%A9mant" title="CrÃ©mant" class="mw-redirect">CrÃ©mant</a></span></h5>
<dl>
<dd>French sparkling wine not made in Champagne region.</dd>
</dl>
<p><a name="Cru" id="Cru"></a></p>
<h5><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Glossary_of_wine_terms&amp;action=edit&amp;section=52" title="Edit section: Cru">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline">Cru</span></h5>
<dl>
<dd>A French term that literally means "growth". May refer to a vineyard or a winery.</dd>
</dl>
<p><a name="Cru_Bourgeois" id="Cru_Bourgeois"></a></p>
<h5><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Glossary_of_wine_terms&amp;action=edit&amp;section=53" title="Edit section: Cru Bourgeois">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline"><a href="/wiki/Cru_Bourgeois" title="Cru Bourgeois">Cru Bourgeois</a></span></h5>
<dl>
<dd>A classification of <a href="/wiki/Bordeaux_wine" title="Bordeaux wine">Bordeaux wine</a> estates in the <a href="/wiki/Medoc" title="Medoc" class="mw-redirect">Medoc</a> that were not part of the originally <a href="/wiki/1855_Bordeaux_classification" title="1855 Bordeaux classification" class="mw-redirect">1855 Bordeaux classification</a>.</dd>
</dl>
<p><a name="Cru_Class.C3.A9" id="Cru_Class.C3.A9"></a></p>
<h5><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Glossary_of_wine_terms&amp;action=edit&amp;section=54" title="Edit section: Cru ClassÃ©">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline">Cru ClassÃ©</span></h5>
<dl>
<dd>A French term for an officially classified vineyard or winery.</dd>
</dl>
<p><a name="C.S." id="C.S."></a></p>
<h5><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Glossary_of_wine_terms&amp;action=edit&amp;section=55" title="Edit section: C.S.">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline">C.S.</span></h5>
<dl>
<dd>An Italian abbreviation for <i>Cantina Sociale</i> that appears on wine labels denoting that the wine has been made by a local cooperative.</dd>
</dl>
<p><a name="Cult_wines" id="Cult_wines"></a></p>
<h5><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Glossary_of_wine_terms&amp;action=edit&amp;section=56" title="Edit section: Cult wines">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline"><a href="/wiki/Cult_wines" title="Cult wines">Cult wines</a></span></h5>
<dl>
<dd>Wines for which committed buyers will pay large sums of money because of their desirability and rarity.</dd>
</dl>
<p><a name="Cuvaison" id="Cuvaison"></a></p>
<h5><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Glossary_of_wine_terms&amp;action=edit&amp;section=57" title="Edit section: Cuvaison">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline"><a href="/wiki/Cuvaison" title="Cuvaison" class="mw-redirect">Cuvaison</a></span></h5>
<dl>
<dd>The French term for the period of time during <a href="/wiki/Fermentation_(wine)" title="Fermentation (wine)">alcoholic fermentation</a> when the wine is in contact with the solid matter such as skin, pips, stalks, in in order to extract colour, flavour and <a href="/wiki/Glossary_of_wine_terms#T" title="Glossary of wine terms">tannin</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-wdglossC_5-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-wdglossC-5" title=""><span>[</span>6<span>]</span></a></sup> See also <a href="/wiki/Maceration" title="Maceration">maceration</a>.</dd>
</dl>
<p><a name="Cuv.C3.A9e" id="Cuv.C3.A9e"></a></p>
<h5><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Glossary_of_wine_terms&amp;action=edit&amp;section=58" title="Edit section: CuvÃ©e">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline"><a href="/wiki/Cuv%C3%A9e" title="CuvÃ©e">CuvÃ©e</a></span></h5>
<dl>
<dd>French term, meaning vat or tank. On wine labels it is used to denote wine of a specific blend or batch.</dd>
</dl>
<p><a name="Cuverie" id="Cuverie"></a></p>
<h5><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Glossary_of_wine_terms&amp;action=edit&amp;section=59" title="Edit section: Cuverie">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline">Cuverie</span></h5>
<dl>
<dd>French term, along with <b>Cuvier</b> that refers to the building or room where fermentation takes place.</dd>
</dl>
<p><a name="C.V." id="C.V."></a></p>
<h5><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Glossary_of_wine_terms&amp;action=edit&amp;section=60" title="Edit section: C.V.">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline">C.V.</span></h5>
<dl>
<dd>Abbreviation for the French term <i>CoopÃ©rative de <a href="/wiki/Vigneron" title="Vigneron">Vignerons</a></i> that may appear on wine labels to denote that the wine has been made by a local cooperative.</dd>
</dl>
<p><a name="D" id="D"></a></p>
<h2><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Glossary_of_wine_terms&amp;action=edit&amp;section=61" title="Edit section: D">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline">D</span></h2>
<p><a name="Decanting" id="Decanting"></a></p>
<h5><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Glossary_of_wine_terms&amp;action=edit&amp;section=62" title="Edit section: Decanting">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline">Decanting</span></h5>
<dl>
<dd>The process of pouring wine from its bottle into a <a href="/wiki/Decanter" title="Decanter">decanter</a> to separate the sediment from the wine.</dd>
</dl>
<p><a name="Dessert_wine" id="Dessert_wine"></a></p>
<h5><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Glossary_of_wine_terms&amp;action=edit&amp;section=63" title="Edit section: Dessert wine">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline"><a href="/wiki/Dessert_wine" title="Dessert wine">Dessert wine</a></span></h5>
<dl>
<dd>Varies by region. In the UK, a very sweet, low alcohol wine. In the US by law, any wine containing over 15% alcohol.</dd>
</dl>
<p><a name="DO" id="DO"></a></p>
<h5><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Glossary_of_wine_terms&amp;action=edit&amp;section=64" title="Edit section: DO">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline">DO</span></h5>
<dl>
<dd>1. The abbreviation for <i><b><a href="/wiki/Denominaci%C3%B3n_de_Origen" title="DenominaciÃ³n de Origen">DenominaciÃ³n de Origen</a></b></i>, or "place name". This is <a href="/wiki/Spain" title="Spain">Spain</a>'s designation for wines whose name, origin of grapes, grape varieties and other important factors are regulated by law.<br />
2. The abbreviation for <b><a href="/wiki/Dissolved_oxygen" title="Dissolved oxygen" class="mw-redirect">dissolved oxygen</a></b>, the degree of oxygen saturation in a wine, which strongly affects oxidation of the wine and its ageing properties.</dd>
</dl>
<p><a name="DOC" id="DOC"></a></p>
<h5><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Glossary_of_wine_terms&amp;action=edit&amp;section=65" title="Edit section: DOC">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline"><a href="/wiki/Denominazione_di_Origine_Controllata" title="Denominazione di Origine Controllata" class="mw-redirect">DOC</a></span></h5>
<dl>
<dd>The abbreviation for <i><b><a href="/wiki/Denominazione_di_Origine_Controllata" title="Denominazione di Origine Controllata" class="mw-redirect">Denominazione di Origine Controllata</a></b></i>, or "controlled place name." This is <a href="/wiki/Italian_wine" title="Italian wine">Italy</a>'s designation for wine whose name, origin of grapes, grape varieties and other important factors are regulated by law. It is also the abbreviation for <a href="/wiki/Portuguese_wine" title="Portuguese wine">Portugal</a>'s highest wine category, which has the same meaning in that country.</dd>
</dl>
<p><a name="DOCG" id="DOCG"></a></p>
<h5><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Glossary_of_wine_terms&amp;action=edit&amp;section=66" title="Edit section: DOCG">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline"><a href="/wiki/DOCG" title="DOCG" class="mw-redirect">DOCG</a></span></h5>
<dl>
<dd>The abbreviation for <i><b><a href="/wiki/DOCG" title="DOCG" class="mw-redirect">Denominazione di Origine Controllata e Garantita</a></b></i>, or controlled and guaranteed place name, which is the category for the highest-ranking wine in <a href="/wiki/Italian_wine" title="Italian wine">Italy</a>.</dd>
</dl>
<p><a name="Drip_dickey" id="Drip_dickey"></a></p>
<h5><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Glossary_of_wine_terms&amp;action=edit&amp;section=67" title="Edit section: Drip dickey">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline"><a href="/wiki/Drip_dickey" title="Drip dickey">Drip dickey</a></span></h5>
<dl>
<dd>A <a href="/wiki/Wine_accessory" title="Wine accessory">wine accessory</a> that slips over the neck of a wine bottle and absorbs any drips that may run down the bottle after pouring - preventing stains to table cloths, counter tops or other surfaces.</dd>
</dl>
<p><a name="E" id="E"></a></p>
<h2><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Glossary_of_wine_terms&amp;action=edit&amp;section=68" title="Edit section: E">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline">E</span></h2>
<p><a name="Eau-de-Vie" id="Eau-de-Vie"></a></p>
<h5><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Glossary_of_wine_terms&amp;action=edit&amp;section=69" title="Edit section: Eau-de-Vie">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline">Eau-de-Vie</span></h5>
<dl>
<dd>French term for a grape-derived <a href="/wiki/Spirit" title="Spirit">spirit</a> such as <a href="/wiki/Brandy" title="Brandy">brandy</a>. Its literal translation is <i>"water of life"</i></dd>
</dl>
<p><a name="Edelf.C3.A4ule" id="Edelf.C3.A4ule"></a></p>
<h5><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Glossary_of_wine_terms&amp;action=edit&amp;section=70" title="Edit section: EdelfÃ¤ule">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline">EdelfÃ¤ule</span></h5>
<dl>
<dd>German term for <a href="/wiki/Noble_rot" title="Noble rot">noble rot</a></dd>
</dl>
<p><a name="Edelkeur" id="Edelkeur"></a></p>
<h5><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Glossary_of_wine_terms&amp;action=edit&amp;section=71" title="Edit section: Edelkeur">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline">Edelkeur</span></h5>
<dl>
<dd><a href="/wiki/South_African_(wine)" title="South African (wine)" class="mw-redirect">South African</a> term for noble rot.</dd>
</dl>
<p><a name="Einzellage.3D" id="Einzellage.3D"></a></p>
<h5><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Glossary_of_wine_terms&amp;action=edit&amp;section=72" title="Edit section: Einzellage=">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline"><a href="/wiki/Einzellage" title="Einzellage" class="mw-redirect">Einzellage</a>=</span></h5>
<dl>
<dd>The smallest geographical unit in <a href="/wiki/German_wine" title="German wine">German wine</a> law representing a single vineyard.</dd>
</dl>
<p><a name="Eiswein" id="Eiswein"></a></p>
<h5><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Glossary_of_wine_terms&amp;action=edit&amp;section=73" title="Edit section: Eiswein">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline"><a href="/wiki/Eiswein" title="Eiswein" class="mw-redirect">Eiswein</a></span></h5>
<dl>
<dd><a href="/wiki/German_language" title="German language">German</a> for <a href="/wiki/Ice_wine" title="Ice wine">ice wine</a>, a <a href="/wiki/Dessert_wine" title="Dessert wine">dessert wine</a> made from frozen grapes.</dd>
</dl>
<p><a name=".C3.89lev.C3.A9_en_f.C3.BBts_de_ch.C3.AAne" id=".C3.89lev.C3.A9_en_f.C3.BBts_de_ch.C3.AAne"></a></p>
<h5><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Glossary_of_wine_terms&amp;action=edit&amp;section=74" title="Edit section: Ã‰levÃ© en fÃ»ts de chÃªne">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline">Ã‰levÃ© en fÃ»ts de chÃªne</span></h5>
<dl>
<dd>French phrase that may appear on wine labels to denote that the wine has been aged in <a href="/wiki/Oak_(wine)" title="Oak (wine)">oak barrels</a>.</dd>
</dl>
<p><a name=".C3.89levage" id=".C3.89levage"></a></p>
<h5><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Glossary_of_wine_terms&amp;action=edit&amp;section=75" title="Edit section: Ã‰levage">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline">Ã‰levage</span></h5>
<dl>
<dd>French term that describes the historical role that <i><a href="/wiki/Negociants" title="Negociants" class="mw-redirect">negociants</a></i> play in the winemaking process-roughly translating as "bringing up" or "raising" the wine. Traditionally <i>negociants</i> would buy ready made wines after <a href="/wiki/Fermentation_(wine)" title="Fermentation (wine)">fermentation</a>, blend and then store the wine before bringing them to the market.</dd>
</dl>
<p><a name="En_primeur" id="En_primeur"></a></p>
<h5><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Glossary_of_wine_terms&amp;action=edit&amp;section=76" title="Edit section: En primeur">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline"><a href="/wiki/En_primeur" title="En primeur" class="mw-redirect">En primeur</a></span></h5>
<dl>
<dd>A system commonly associated with <a href="/wiki/Bordeaux_wine" title="Bordeaux wine">Bordeaux wine</a> were the previous year's <a href="/wiki/Harvest_(wine)" title="Harvest (wine)">harvest</a> is available for contract sales several months before the wine will be bottled and release.</dd>
</dl>
<p><a name="Enc.C3.A9pagement" id="Enc.C3.A9pagement"></a></p>
<h5><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Glossary_of_wine_terms&amp;action=edit&amp;section=77" title="Edit section: EncÃ©pagement">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline">EncÃ©pagement</span></h5>
<dl>
<dd>French term for the proportion of grape varieties used in a blend.</dd>
</dl>
<p><a name="Entry-level_wine" id="Entry-level_wine"></a></p>
<h5><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Glossary_of_wine_terms&amp;action=edit&amp;section=78" title="Edit section: Entry-level wine">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline">Entry-level wine</span></h5>
<dl>
<dd>The wine from a producer's portfolio that is the lowest cost for purchase and offers the most basic quality.</dd>
</dl>
<p><a name="Estate_winery" id="Estate_winery"></a></p>
<h5><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Glossary_of_wine_terms&amp;action=edit&amp;section=79" title="Edit section: Estate winery">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline"><a href="/wiki/Winery" title="Winery">Estate winery</a></span></h5>
<dl>
<dd>A United States winery license allowing farms to produce and sell wine on-site, sometimes known as a farm winery.</dd>
</dl>
<p><a name="EU_lot_number" id="EU_lot_number"></a></p>
<h5><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Glossary_of_wine_terms&amp;action=edit&amp;section=80" title="Edit section: EU lot number">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline"><a href="/wiki/EU" title="EU" class="mw-redirect">EU</a> lot number</span></h5>
<dl>
<dd>A European Union directive initiated in 1992 that mandates every bottle of wine produced or sold in the European Union to include a designated lot number. This allows identified defective or <a href="/wiki/Wine_fraud" title="Wine fraud">fraudulent</a> wine to be tracked and removed from circulation more efficiently.</dd>
</dl>
<p><a name="Ex-cellars" id="Ex-cellars"></a></p>
<h5><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Glossary_of_wine_terms&amp;action=edit&amp;section=81" title="Edit section: Ex-cellars">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline">Ex-cellars</span></h5>
<dl>
<dd>Refers to the extra cost associated with buying wines <i>en primeur</i> that may include the cost of shipping to the <a href="/wiki/Importer" title="Importer" class="mw-redirect">importer</a>'s cellars as well applicable <a href="/wiki/Duties" title="Duties" class="mw-redirect">duties</a> and <a href="/wiki/Taxes" title="Taxes" class="mw-redirect">taxes</a>.</dd>
</dl>
<p><a name="F" id="F"></a></p>
<h2><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Glossary_of_wine_terms&amp;action=edit&amp;section=82" title="Edit section: F">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline">F</span></h2>
<p><a name="Farm_winery" id="Farm_winery"></a></p>
<h5><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Glossary_of_wine_terms&amp;action=edit&amp;section=83" title="Edit section: Farm winery">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline"><a href="/wiki/Farm_winery" title="Farm winery" class="mw-redirect">Farm winery</a></span></h5>
<dl>
<dd>A United States winery license allowing <a href="/wiki/Farm" title="Farm">farms</a> to produce and sell wine on-site.</dd>
</dl>
<p><a name="Fiasco" id="Fiasco"></a></p>
<h5><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Glossary_of_wine_terms&amp;action=edit&amp;section=84" title="Edit section: Fiasco">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline"><a href="/wiki/Fiasco_(bottle)" title="Fiasco (bottle)">Fiasco</a></span></h5>
<dl>
<dd>The straw-covered flask historically associated with <a href="/wiki/Chianti" title="Chianti">Chianti</a>.</dd>
</dl>
<p><a name="Fighting_varietal" id="Fighting_varietal"></a></p>
<h5><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Glossary_of_wine_terms&amp;action=edit&amp;section=85" title="Edit section: Fighting varietal">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline"><a href="/wiki/Fighting_varietal" title="Fighting varietal">Fighting varietal</a></span></h5>
<dl>
<dd>A term that originated in California during the mid 1980s to refer to any inexpensive cork-finished varietal wine in a 1.5 liter bottle.</dd>
</dl>
<p><a name="Fine_wine" id="Fine_wine"></a></p>
<h5><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Glossary_of_wine_terms&amp;action=edit&amp;section=86" title="Edit section: Fine wine">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline">Fine wine</span></h5>
<dl>
<dd>The highest category of wine quality, representing only a very small percentage of worldwide production of wine.</dd>
</dl>
<p><a name="Flagon" id="Flagon"></a></p>
<h5><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Glossary_of_wine_terms&amp;action=edit&amp;section=87" title="Edit section: Flagon">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline">Flagon</span></h5>
<dl>
<dd>A glass bottle that holds two litres of (usually inexpensive) table wine.</dd>
</dl>
<p><a name="Flying_winemaker" id="Flying_winemaker"></a></p>
<h5><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Glossary_of_wine_terms&amp;action=edit&amp;section=88" title="Edit section: Flying winemaker">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline"><a href="/wiki/Flying_winemaker" title="Flying winemaker" class="mw-redirect">Flying winemaker</a></span></h5>
<dl>
<dd>A winemaker who travels extensively across the globe, sharing techniques and technology from one region of the world to another. The term originated with <a href="/wiki/Australian_(wine)" title="Australian (wine)" class="mw-redirect">Australian</a> winemakers who would fly to <a href="/wiki/Northern_Hemisphere" title="Northern Hemisphere">Northern Hemisphere</a> wine regions in <a href="/wiki/Europe" title="Europe">Europe</a> and the <a href="/wiki/United_States_(wine)" title="United States (wine)" class="mw-redirect">United States</a> during the August-October <a href="/wiki/Harvest_time_(wine)" title="Harvest time (wine)" class="mw-redirect">harvest time</a> when viticulture in the <a href="/wiki/Southern_Hemisphere" title="Southern Hemisphere">Southern Hemisphere</a> is relatively quiet.</dd>
</dl>
<p><a name="Fortified_wine" id="Fortified_wine"></a></p>
<h5><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Glossary_of_wine_terms&amp;action=edit&amp;section=89" title="Edit section: Fortified wine">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline"><a href="/wiki/Fortified_wine" title="Fortified wine">Fortified wine</a></span></h5>
<dl>
<dd>Wine to which alcohol has been added, generally to increase the concentration to a high enough level to prevent fermentation.</dd>
</dl>
<p><a name="French_Paradox" id="French_Paradox"></a></p>
<h5><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Glossary_of_wine_terms&amp;action=edit&amp;section=90" title="Edit section: French Paradox">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline"><a href="/wiki/French_Paradox" title="French Paradox" class="mw-redirect">French Paradox</a></span></h5>
<dl>
<dd>An 1991 episode of the American news program <i><a href="/wiki/60_Minutes" title="60 Minutes">60 Minutes</a></i> that documented the low <a href="/wiki/Mortality_rate" title="Mortality rate">mortality rate</a> from <a href="/wiki/Cardiovascular_disease" title="Cardiovascular disease">cardiovascular disease</a> among the <a href="/wiki/French_(people)" title="French (people)" class="mw-redirect">French</a> who had a high-alcohol, high-<a href="/wiki/Cholesterol" title="Cholesterol">cholesterol</a> and low exercise lifestyle in contrast to the high mortality rate among Americans with a relatively lower cholesterol, low alcohol and more exercise lifestyle.</dd>
</dl>
<p><a name="Frizzante" id="Frizzante"></a></p>
<h5><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Glossary_of_wine_terms&amp;action=edit&amp;section=91" title="Edit section: Frizzante">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline"><a href="/wiki/Frizzante" title="Frizzante" class="mw-redirect">Frizzante</a></span></h5>
<dl>
<dd>Italian term for a semi-<a href="/wiki/Sparkling_wine" title="Sparkling wine">sparkling wine</a>.</dd>
</dl>
<p><a name="Frizzantino" id="Frizzantino"></a></p>
<h5><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Glossary_of_wine_terms&amp;action=edit&amp;section=92" title="Edit section: Frizzantino">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline"><a href="/wiki/Frizzantino" title="Frizzantino" class="mw-redirect">Frizzantino</a></span></h5>
<dl>
<dd>Italian term for a wine that has very slight <a href="/wiki/Effervescence" title="Effervescence">effervescence</a>, more than a still wine but less than a semi-sparkling. Similar to the French term <i>perlant</i>.</dd>
</dl>
<p><a name="Fruit_wine" id="Fruit_wine"></a></p>
<h5><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Glossary_of_wine_terms&amp;action=edit&amp;section=93" title="Edit section: Fruit wine">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline"><a href="/wiki/Fruit_wine" title="Fruit wine">Fruit wine</a></span></h5>
<dl>
<dd>A fermented alcoholic beverage made from non-grape fruit juice which may or may not include the addition of sugar or honey. Fruit wines are always called "something" wines (e.g., plum wine), since the word wine alone is often legally defined as a beverage made only from grapes.</dd>
</dl>
<p><a name="G" id="G"></a></p>
<h2><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Glossary_of_wine_terms&amp;action=edit&amp;section=94" title="Edit section: G">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline">G</span></h2>
<p><a name="Globalization_of_wine" id="Globalization_of_wine"></a></p>
<h5><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Glossary_of_wine_terms&amp;action=edit&amp;section=95" title="Edit section: Globalization of wine">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline"><a href="/wiki/Globalization_of_wine" title="Globalization of wine">Globalization of wine</a></span></h5>
<dl>
<dd>Refers to the increasingly international nature of the wine industry, including <a href="/wiki/Vineyard" title="Vineyard">vineyard</a> management practices, winemaking techniques, wine styles, and wine marketing.</dd>
</dl>
<p><a name="Grande_Marque" id="Grande_Marque"></a></p>
<h5><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Glossary_of_wine_terms&amp;action=edit&amp;section=96" title="Edit section: Grande Marque">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline">Grande Marque</span></h5>
<dl>
<dd>French term for a famous <a href="/wiki/Brand" title="Brand">brand</a> of wine, most commonly associated with the large <a href="/wiki/Champagne_houses" title="Champagne houses" class="mw-redirect">Champagne houses</a>.</dd>
</dl>
<p><a name="Grand_cru" id="Grand_cru"></a></p>
<h5><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Glossary_of_wine_terms&amp;action=edit&amp;section=97" title="Edit section: Grand cru">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline"><a href="/wiki/Grand_cru" title="Grand cru">Grand cru</a></span></h5>
<dl>
<dd>French term for a "Great growth" or vineyard. In <a href="/wiki/Burgundy_(wine)" title="Burgundy (wine)" class="mw-redirect">Burgundy</a>, the term is regulated to a define list of <a href="/wiki/List_of_Burgundy_Grand_Crus" title="List of Burgundy Grand Crus">Grand cru vineyards</a>.</dd>
</dl>
<p><a name="Grand_vin" id="Grand_vin"></a></p>
<h5><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Glossary_of_wine_terms&amp;action=edit&amp;section=98" title="Edit section: Grand vin">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline">Grand vin</span></h5>
<dl>
<dd>French term most often associated with <a href="/wiki/Bordeaux_(wine)" title="Bordeaux (wine)" class="mw-redirect">Bordeaux</a> where it denotes a Chateau's premier wine, or "first wine". On a <a href="/wiki/Wine_label" title="Wine label">wine label</a>, the word's <i>Grand vin</i> may appear to help distinguish the wine from an estate's <a href="/wiki/Second_(wine)" title="Second (wine)" class="mw-redirect">second</a> or third wine.</dd>
</dl>
<p><a name="Grosslage" id="Grosslage"></a></p>
<h5><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Glossary_of_wine_terms&amp;action=edit&amp;section=99" title="Edit section: Grosslage">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline"><a href="/wiki/Grosslage" title="Grosslage" class="mw-redirect">Grosslage</a></span></h5>
<dl>
<dd>A German designation for a cluster of vineyards within a <a href="/wiki/Bereich" title="Bereich" class="mw-redirect">Bereich</a>.</dd>
</dl>
<p><a name="H" id="H"></a></p>
<h2><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Glossary_of_wine_terms&amp;action=edit&amp;section=100" title="Edit section: H">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline">H</span></h2>
<p><a name="Hock" id="Hock"></a></p>
<h5><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Glossary_of_wine_terms&amp;action=edit&amp;section=101" title="Edit section: Hock">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline"><a href="/wiki/Hock_(wine)" title="Hock (wine)">Hock</a></span></h5>
<dl>
<dd>Term for <a href="/wiki/Rhine" title="Rhine">Rhine</a> wines, usually used in England.</dd>
</dl>
<p><a name="Horizontal_wine_tasting" id="Horizontal_wine_tasting"></a></p>
<h5><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Glossary_of_wine_terms&amp;action=edit&amp;section=102" title="Edit section: Horizontal wine tasting">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline"><a href="/wiki/Horizontal_wine_tasting" title="Horizontal wine tasting" class="mw-redirect">Horizontal wine tasting</a></span></h5>
<dl>
<dd>A tasting of a group of wines from the same vintage or representing the same style of wine (such as all <a href="/wiki/Pinot_noirs" title="Pinot noirs" class="mw-redirect">Pinot noirs</a> or all <a href="/wiki/Washington_wine" title="Washington wine">Washington wines</a>) as oppose to a vertical tasting which consist of the same wine through different vintages,</dd>
</dl>
<p><a name="I" id="I"></a></p>
<h2><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Glossary_of_wine_terms&amp;action=edit&amp;section=103" title="Edit section: I">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline">I</span></h2>
<p><a name="Ice_wine" id="Ice_wine"></a></p>
<h5><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Glossary_of_wine_terms&amp;action=edit&amp;section=104" title="Edit section: Ice wine">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline"><a href="/wiki/Ice_wine" title="Ice wine">Ice wine</a></span></h5>
<dl>
<dd>Wine made from frozen grapes. Written, and trademarked as a single word - Icewine - in Canada. Called <i>Eiswein</i> in <a href="/wiki/German_language" title="German language">German</a>.</dd>
</dl>
<p><a name="IGT" id="IGT"></a></p>
<h5><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Glossary_of_wine_terms&amp;action=edit&amp;section=105" title="Edit section: IGT">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline"><a href="/wiki/Indicazione_Geografica_Tipica" title="Indicazione Geografica Tipica" class="mw-redirect">IGT</a></span></h5>
<dl>
<dd>Abbreviation for "<i>Indicazione Geografica Tipica</i>", the lowest-ranking of the three categories of <a href="/wiki/Italian_wine" title="Italian wine">Italian wine</a> regulated by <a href="/wiki/Italy" title="Italy">Italian</a> law.</dd>
</dl>
<p><a name="International_variety" id="International_variety"></a></p>
<h5><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Glossary_of_wine_terms&amp;action=edit&amp;section=106" title="Edit section: International variety">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline"><a href="/wiki/International_variety" title="International variety">International variety</a></span></h5>
<dl>
<dd><a href="/wiki/Grape_varieties" title="Grape varieties" class="mw-redirect">Grape varieties</a> grown in nearly every major wine region, for example <a href="/wiki/Cabernet_Sauvignon" title="Cabernet Sauvignon">Cabernet Sauvignon</a>, <a href="/wiki/Chardonnay" title="Chardonnay">Chardonnay</a> and <a href="/wiki/Merlot" title="Merlot">Merlot</a></dd>
</dl>
<p><a name="J" id="J"></a></p>
<h2><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Glossary_of_wine_terms&amp;action=edit&amp;section=107" title="Edit section: J">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline">J</span></h2>
<p><a name="Jeroboam" id="Jeroboam"></a></p>
<h5><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Glossary_of_wine_terms&amp;action=edit&amp;section=108" title="Edit section: Jeroboam">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline">Jeroboam</span></h5>
<dl>
<dd>A large bottle holding three <a href="/wiki/Litre" title="Litre">litres</a>, the equivalent of four regular <a href="/wiki/Wine_bottle" title="Wine bottle">wine bottles</a>.</dd>
</dl>
<p><a name="Jug_wine" id="Jug_wine"></a></p>
<h5><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Glossary_of_wine_terms&amp;action=edit&amp;section=109" title="Edit section: Jug wine">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline">Jug wine</span></h5>
<dl>
<dd><a href="/wiki/American_English" title="American English">American</a> term for inexpensive table wine (<a href="/wiki/French_language" title="French language">French</a>: <span lang="fr" xml:lang="fr"><i>Vin de table</i></span>).</dd>
</dl>
<p><a name="K" id="K"></a></p>
<h2><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Glossary_of_wine_terms&amp;action=edit&amp;section=110" title="Edit section: K">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline">K</span></h2>
<p><a name="Kabinett" id="Kabinett"></a></p>
<h5><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Glossary_of_wine_terms&amp;action=edit&amp;section=111" title="Edit section: Kabinett">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline"><a href="/wiki/Kabinett" title="Kabinett">Kabinett</a></span></h5>
<dl>
<dd>A wine designation in Germany (where it is a PrÃ¤dikat) and Austria.</dd>
</dl>
<p><a name="Kosher_wine" id="Kosher_wine"></a></p>
<h5><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Glossary_of_wine_terms&amp;action=edit&amp;section=112" title="Edit section: Kosher wine">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline"><a href="/wiki/Kosher_wine" title="Kosher wine">Kosher wine</a></span></h5>
<dl>
<dd>Wine that is produced under the supervision of a <a href="/wiki/Rabbi" title="Rabbi">rabbi</a> so as to be ritually pure or clean.</dd>
</dl>
<p><a name="L" id="L"></a></p>
<h2><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Glossary_of_wine_terms&amp;action=edit&amp;section=113" title="Edit section: L">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline">L</span></h2>
<p><a name="Landwein" id="Landwein"></a></p>
<h5><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Glossary_of_wine_terms&amp;action=edit&amp;section=114" title="Edit section: Landwein">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline"><a href="/wiki/Landwein" title="Landwein" class="mw-redirect">Landwein</a></span></h5>
<dl>
<dd>German term for a wine slightly above <a href="/wiki/Table_wine" title="Table wine">table wines</a> (tafelwine). Similar to a French <i><a href="/wiki/Vin_de_pays" title="Vin de pays">vin de pays</a></i> wine.</dd>
</dl>
<p><a name="Late_harvest_wine" id="Late_harvest_wine"></a></p>
<h5><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Glossary_of_wine_terms&amp;action=edit&amp;section=115" title="Edit section: Late harvest wine">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline"><a href="/wiki/Late_harvest_wine" title="Late harvest wine">Late harvest wine</a></span></h5>
<dl>
<dd>Also known as <b>late picked</b>, wine made from grapes that have been left on the vine longer than usual. Usually an indicator for a very sweet or <a href="/wiki/Dessert_wine" title="Dessert wine">dessert wine</a>.</dd>
</dl>
<p><a name="Lie" id="Lie"></a></p>
<h5><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Glossary_of_wine_terms&amp;action=edit&amp;section=116" title="Edit section: Lie">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline">Lie</span></h5>
<dl>
<dd>French term for the dead yeast and sediment of wine also known as <i><a href="/wiki/Lees_(wine)" title="Lees (wine)" class="mw-redirect">lees</a></i>.</dd>
</dl>
<p><a name="Litre_.28US_-_Liter.29" id="Litre_.28US_-_Liter.29"></a></p>
<h5><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Glossary_of_wine_terms&amp;action=edit&amp;section=117" title="Edit section: Litre (US - Liter)">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline"><a href="/wiki/Litre" title="Litre">Litre</a> (<a href="/wiki/American_English" title="American English">US</a> - <a href="/wiki/Liter" title="Liter" class="mw-redirect">Liter</a>)</span></h5>
<dl>
<dd>A <a href="/wiki/Metric_system" title="Metric system">metric</a> measure of volume equal to 33.8 <a href="/wiki/Fluid_ounce" title="Fluid ounce">fluid ounces</a> (U.S.) or 35.2 fl oz (imperial).</dd>
</dl>
<p><a name="Lieu-dit" id="Lieu-dit"></a></p>
<h5><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Glossary_of_wine_terms&amp;action=edit&amp;section=118" title="Edit section: Lieu-dit">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline"><a href="/wiki/Lieu-dit" title="Lieu-dit">Lieu-dit</a></span></h5>
<dl>
<dd>French term for a named vineyard site. Usually used in the context of describing individual vineyards below <a href="/wiki/Grand_cru" title="Grand cru">Grand cru</a> status.</dd>
</dl>
<p><a name="Liquoreux" id="Liquoreux"></a></p>
<h5><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Glossary_of_wine_terms&amp;action=edit&amp;section=119" title="Edit section: Liquoreux">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline">Liquoreux</span></h5>
<dl>
<dd>French term meaning <i>"<a href="/wiki/Liqueur" title="Liqueur">liqueur</a>-like"</i> used to describe <a href="/wiki/Dessert_wine" title="Dessert wine">dessert wine</a> with a luscious, almost unctuous, quality.</dd>
</dl>
<p><a name="M" id="M"></a></p>
<h2><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Glossary_of_wine_terms&amp;action=edit&amp;section=120" title="Edit section: M">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline">M</span></h2>
<p><a name="Magnum" id="Magnum"></a></p>
<h5><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Glossary_of_wine_terms&amp;action=edit&amp;section=121" title="Edit section: Magnum">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline"><a href="/wiki/Magnum" title="Magnum">Magnum</a></span></h5>
<dl>
<dd>A bottle holding 1.5 <a href="/wiki/Litre" title="Litre">litres</a>, the equivalent of two regular <a href="/wiki/Wine_bottle" title="Wine bottle">wine bottles</a>.</dd>
</dl>
<p><a name="Master_of_Wine" id="Master_of_Wine"></a></p>
<h5><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Glossary_of_wine_terms&amp;action=edit&amp;section=122" title="Edit section: Master of Wine">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline"><a href="/wiki/Master_of_Wine" title="Master of Wine">Master of Wine</a></span></h5>
<dl>
<dd>A qualification (not an academic degree) conferred by The Institute of Masters of Wine, which is located in the United Kingdom.</dd>
</dl>
<p><a name="May_wine" id="May_wine"></a></p>
<h5><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Glossary_of_wine_terms&amp;action=edit&amp;section=123" title="Edit section: May wine">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline"><a href="/wiki/May_wine" title="May wine">May wine</a></span></h5>
<dl>
<dd>A light German wine flavored with sweet <a href="/wiki/Woodruff" title="Woodruff">woodruff</a> in addition to strawberries or other fruit.</dd>
</dl>
<p><a name="Mead" id="Mead"></a></p>
<h5><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Glossary_of_wine_terms&amp;action=edit&amp;section=124" title="Edit section: Mead">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline"><a href="/wiki/Mead" title="Mead">Mead</a></span></h5>
<dl>
<dd>A wine-like alcoholic beverage made of fermented <a href="/wiki/Honey" title="Honey">honey</a> and water rather than grape juice.</dd>
</dl>
<p><a name="Meritage" id="Meritage"></a></p>
<h5><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Glossary_of_wine_terms&amp;action=edit&amp;section=125" title="Edit section: Meritage">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline"><a href="/wiki/Meritage" title="Meritage">Meritage</a></span></h5>
<dl>
<dd>Originally created in California, these blended wines can be summed up as the "American Bordeaux". The Red blend is made from at least 2 of the 5 Bordeaux grape varieties: Cabernet Sauvignon, Merlot, Cabernet Franc, Petit Verdot, and Malbec. The White Meritage is a blend at least 2 of Sauvignon Blanc, Sauvignon Vert, and Semillon.</dd>
</dl>
<p><a name="Methuselah" id="Methuselah"></a></p>
<h5><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Glossary_of_wine_terms&amp;action=edit&amp;section=126" title="Edit section: Methuselah">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline">Methuselah</span></h5>
<dl>
<dd>A large bottle holding six <a href="/wiki/Litre" title="Litre">litres</a>, the equivalent of eight regular <a href="/wiki/Wine_bottle" title="Wine bottle">wine bottles</a>.</dd>
</dl>
<p><a name="Mis_en_bouteille_au_ch.C3.A2teau" id="Mis_en_bouteille_au_ch.C3.A2teau"></a></p>
<h5><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Glossary_of_wine_terms&amp;action=edit&amp;section=127" title="Edit section: Mis en bouteille au chÃ¢teau">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline">Mis en bouteille au chÃ¢teau</span></h5>
<dl>
<dd>French for "<i>bottled at the winery</i>", usually in <a href="/wiki/Bordeaux_(wine)" title="Bordeaux (wine)" class="mw-redirect">Bordeaux</a>.</dd>
</dl>
<p><a name="Moelleux" id="Moelleux"></a></p>
<h5><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Glossary_of_wine_terms&amp;action=edit&amp;section=128" title="Edit section: Moelleux">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline">Moelleux</span></h5>
<dl>
<dd>French term usually used to describe wines of mid level sweetness or <a href="/w/index.php?title=Liquoreux&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1" class="new" title="Liquoreux (page does not exist)">liquoreux</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-Oxford_pg_446_6-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Oxford_pg_446-6" title=""><span>[</span>7<span>]</span></a></sup></dd>
</dl>
<p><a name="Monopole" id="Monopole"></a></p>
<h5><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Glossary_of_wine_terms&amp;action=edit&amp;section=129" title="Edit section: Monopole">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline"><a href="/wiki/Monopole" title="Monopole">Monopole</a></span></h5>
<dl>
<dd>French term for a vineyard under single ownership.</dd>
</dl>
<p><a name="Mousse" id="Mousse"></a></p>
<h5><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Glossary_of_wine_terms&amp;action=edit&amp;section=130" title="Edit section: Mousse">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline">Mousse</span></h5>
<dl>
<dd>The sparkling effervescence of a wine. In the glass it perceived as the bubbling but the surface of the glass can affect this perception. Premium quality sparkling wine has a mousse composed of small, persistent string of bubbles.</dd>
</dl>
<p><a name="Mulled_wine" id="Mulled_wine"></a></p>
<h5><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Glossary_of_wine_terms&amp;action=edit&amp;section=131" title="Edit section: Mulled wine">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline"><a href="/wiki/Mulled_wine" title="Mulled wine">Mulled wine</a></span></h5>
<dl>
<dd>Wine that is spiced, heated, and served as a <a href="/wiki/Punch_(drink)" title="Punch (drink)">punch</a>.</dd>
</dl>
<p><a name="N" id="N"></a></p>
<h2><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Glossary_of_wine_terms&amp;action=edit&amp;section=132" title="Edit section: N">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline">N</span></h2>
<p><a name="Nebuchadnezzar" id="Nebuchadnezzar"></a></p>
<h5><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Glossary_of_wine_terms&amp;action=edit&amp;section=133" title="Edit section: Nebuchadnezzar">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline"><a href="/wiki/Nebuchadnezzar_(wine)" title="Nebuchadnezzar (wine)" class="mw-redirect">Nebuchadnezzar</a></span></h5>
<dl>
<dd>A large bottle holding 15 <a href="/wiki/Litre" title="Litre">litres</a>, the equivalent of 20 regular <a href="/wiki/Wine_bottle" title="Wine bottle">wine bottles</a>.</dd>
</dl>
<p><a name="N.C3.A9gociant" id="N.C3.A9gociant"></a></p>
<h5><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Glossary_of_wine_terms&amp;action=edit&amp;section=134" title="Edit section: NÃ©gociant">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline"><a href="/wiki/N%C3%A9gociant" title="NÃ©gociant">NÃ©gociant</a></span></h5>
<dl>
<dd><a href="/wiki/French_language" title="French language">French</a> for "<i>trader</i>". A wine merchant who assembles the produce of smaller growers and winemakers and sells the result under its own name.</dd>
</dl>
<p><a name="New_World_wine" id="New_World_wine"></a></p>
<h5><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Glossary_of_wine_terms&amp;action=edit&amp;section=135" title="Edit section: New World wine">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline"><a href="/wiki/New_World_wine" title="New World wine">New World wine</a></span></h5>
<dl>
<dd>Wines produced outside of the traditional wine growing areas of Europe and North Africa.</dd>
</dl>
<p><a name="Nose" id="Nose"></a></p>
<h5><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Glossary_of_wine_terms&amp;action=edit&amp;section=136" title="Edit section: Nose">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline"><a href="/wiki/Nose_(wine)" title="Nose (wine)" class="mw-redirect">Nose</a></span></h5>
<dl>
<dd>The aroma or bouquet of a wine</dd>
</dl>
<p><a name="O" id="O"></a></p>
<h2><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Glossary_of_wine_terms&amp;action=edit&amp;section=137" title="Edit section: O">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline">O</span></h2>
<p><a name="Oenophile" id="Oenophile"></a></p>
<h5><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Glossary_of_wine_terms&amp;action=edit&amp;section=138" title="Edit section: Oenophile">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline"><a href="/wiki/Oenophile" title="Oenophile" class="mw-redirect">Oenophile</a></span></h5>
<dl>
<dd>A wine <a href="/wiki/Aficionado" title="Aficionado" class="mw-redirect">aficionado</a> or <a href="/wiki/Connoisseur" title="Connoisseur">connoisseur</a>.</dd>
</dl>
<p><a name="Old_World_wine" id="Old_World_wine"></a></p>
<h5><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Glossary_of_wine_terms&amp;action=edit&amp;section=139" title="Edit section: Old World wine">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline"><a href="/wiki/Old_World_wine" title="Old World wine">Old World wine</a></span></h5>
<dl>
<dd>Wines produced inside of the traditional wine growing areas of Europe and North Africa.</dd>
</dl>
<p><a name="Organoleptic" id="Organoleptic"></a></p>
<h5><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Glossary_of_wine_terms&amp;action=edit&amp;section=140" title="Edit section: Organoleptic">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline"><a href="http://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/Organoleptic" class="extiw" title="wikt:Organoleptic">Organoleptic</a></span></h5>
<dl>
<dd>A <a href="/wiki/Winetasting" title="Winetasting" class="mw-redirect">winetasting</a> term for anything that affects one of the main <a href="/wiki/Senses" title="Senses" class="mw-redirect">senses</a> such as smell. An example would be an affliction of the <a href="/wiki/Common_cold" title="Common cold">common cold</a> or being in a room with someone wearing an overwhelming amount of <a href="/wiki/Perfume" title="Perfume">perfume</a>.</dd>
</dl>
<p><a name="P" id="P"></a></p>
<h2><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Glossary_of_wine_terms&amp;action=edit&amp;section=141" title="Edit section: P">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline">P</span></h2>
<p><a name="Petit_Ch.C3.A2teau" id="Petit_Ch.C3.A2teau"></a></p>
<h5><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Glossary_of_wine_terms&amp;action=edit&amp;section=142" title="Edit section: Petit ChÃ¢teau">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline">Petit ChÃ¢teau</span></h5>
<dl>
<dd>A <a href="/wiki/Bordeaux_wine" title="Bordeaux wine">Bordeaux wine</a> estate that doesn't have any official designation of <a href="/wiki/Classification_(Bordeaux)" title="Classification (Bordeaux)" class="mw-redirect">classification</a>.</dd>
</dl>
<p><a name="Piquant" id="Piquant"></a></p>
<h5><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Glossary_of_wine_terms&amp;action=edit&amp;section=143" title="Edit section: Piquant">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline">Piquant</span></h5>
<dl>
<dd>French term for a simple, <a href="/wiki/Quaffing" title="Quaffing" class="mw-redirect">quaffing</a> white wine with pleasing fruit structure and balance of <a href="/wiki/Acidity_(wine)" title="Acidity (wine)" class="mw-redirect">acidity</a>.</dd>
</dl>
<p><a name="Plafond_Limit.C3.A9_de_Classement" id="Plafond_Limit.C3.A9_de_Classement"></a></p>
<h5><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Glossary_of_wine_terms&amp;action=edit&amp;section=144" title="Edit section: Plafond LimitÃ© de Classement">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline">Plafond LimitÃ© de Classement</span></h5>
<dl>
<dd>An allowance within the French <a href="/wiki/AOC_(wine)" title="AOC (wine)" class="mw-redirect">AOC</a> system that allows producers to exceed the official maximum limit on <a href="/wiki/Yields_(wine)" title="Yields (wine)" class="mw-redirect">yields</a> by as much as 20% in warm weather years. Critics such as wine writer <a href="/wiki/Tom_Stevenson" title="Tom Stevenson">Tom Stevenson</a> describes this loophole (also known as "PLC") as "legalized cheating"</dd>
</dl>
<p><a name="Plan_Bordeaux" id="Plan_Bordeaux"></a></p>
<h5><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Glossary_of_wine_terms&amp;action=edit&amp;section=145" title="Edit section: Plan Bordeaux">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline"><a href="/wiki/Plan_Bordeaux" title="Plan Bordeaux">Plan Bordeaux</a></span></h5>
<dl>
<dd>A proposal for enhancing the economic status of the wine industry in Bordeaux.</dd>
</dl>
<p><a name="Plonk" id="Plonk"></a></p>
<h5><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Glossary_of_wine_terms&amp;action=edit&amp;section=146" title="Edit section: Plonk">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline"><a href="/wiki/Plonk_(wine)" title="Plonk (wine)">Plonk</a></span></h5>
<dl>
<dd><a href="/wiki/British_English" title="British English">British English</a> slang for an inexpensive bottle of wine. The term is thought to originate from the <a href="/wiki/French_language" title="French language">French</a> word for white wine, "<i>blanc</i>".</dd>
</dl>
<p><a name="Port" id="Port"></a></p>
<h5><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Glossary_of_wine_terms&amp;action=edit&amp;section=147" title="Edit section: Port">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline"><a href="/wiki/Port_wine" title="Port wine">Port</a></span></h5>
<dl>
<dd>A sweet fortified wine, which is produced from grapes grown and processed in the Douro region of <a href="/wiki/Portugal" title="Portugal">Portugal</a>. This wine is fortified with the addition of distilled grape spirits in order to boost the alcohol content and stop fermentation thus preserving some of the natural grape sugars. Several imitations are made throughout the world.</dd>
</dl>
<p><a name="Pr.C3.A4dikat" id="Pr.C3.A4dikat"></a></p>
<h5><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Glossary_of_wine_terms&amp;action=edit&amp;section=148" title="Edit section: PrÃ¤dikat">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline"><a href="/wiki/Pr%C3%A4dikat" title="PrÃ¤dikat" class="mw-redirect">PrÃ¤dikat</a></span></h5>
<dl>
<dd>A wine designation for high quality used in Germany and Austria, based on grape ripeness and <a href="/wiki/Must_weight" title="Must weight">must weight</a>. There are several <i>PrÃ¤dikate</i> ranging from <a href="/wiki/Kabinett" title="Kabinett">Kabinett</a> (<a href="/wiki/Sp%C3%A4tlese" title="SpÃ¤tlese">SpÃ¤tlese</a> in Austria) to <a href="/wiki/Trockenbeerenauslese" title="Trockenbeerenauslese">Trockenbeerenauslese</a>.</dd>
</dl>
<p><a name="Pr.C3.A4dikatswein" id="Pr.C3.A4dikatswein"></a></p>
<h5><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Glossary_of_wine_terms&amp;action=edit&amp;section=149" title="Edit section: PrÃ¤dikatswein">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline"><a href="/wiki/Pr%C3%A4dikatswein" title="PrÃ¤dikatswein" class="mw-redirect">PrÃ¤dikatswein</a></span></h5>
<dl>
<dd>The highest class of wine in the German wine classification, formerly called <i>QualitÃ¤tswein mit PrÃ¤dikat</i>. These wines always display a specific <i>PrÃ¤dikat</i> on their label.</dd>
</dl>
<p><a name="Premier_cru" id="Premier_cru"></a></p>
<h5><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Glossary_of_wine_terms&amp;action=edit&amp;section=150" title="Edit section: Premier cru">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline"><a href="/wiki/Premier_cru" title="Premier cru" class="mw-redirect">Premier cru</a></span></h5>
<dl>
<dd>French term for a "First growth". Used mostly in conjunction with the wines of <a href="/wiki/Burgundy_(wine)" title="Burgundy (wine)" class="mw-redirect">Burgundy</a> and <a href="/wiki/Champagne_(classification)" title="Champagne (classification)" class="mw-redirect">Champagne</a> where the term is regulated.</dd>
</dl>
<p><a name="Premium_wines" id="Premium_wines"></a></p>
<h5><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Glossary_of_wine_terms&amp;action=edit&amp;section=151" title="Edit section: Premium wines">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline">Premium wines</span></h5>
<dl>
<dd>A subject term to describe a higher quality classification of wine above every day drinking <a href="/wiki/Table_wines" title="Table wines" class="mw-redirect">table wines</a>. While premium wines maybe very expensive there is no set price point that distinguishes when a wine becomes a "premium wine". Premium wines generally have more aging potential than every day <a href="/wiki/Quaffing" title="Quaffing" class="mw-redirect">quaffing</a> wines.</dd>
</dl>
<p><a name="Punt" id="Punt"></a></p>
<h5><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Glossary_of_wine_terms&amp;action=edit&amp;section=152" title="Edit section: Punt">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline">Punt</span></h5>
<dl>
<dd>The indentation found in the base of a wine bottle. Punt depth is often thought to be related to wine quality, with better quality wines having a deeper punt.</dd>
</dl>
<p><a name="Q" id="Q"></a></p>
<h2><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Glossary_of_wine_terms&amp;action=edit&amp;section=153" title="Edit section: Q">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline">Q</span></h2>
<p><a name="QbA" id="QbA"></a></p>
<h5><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Glossary_of_wine_terms&amp;action=edit&amp;section=154" title="Edit section: QbA">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline">QbA</span></h5>
<dl>
<dd>German acronym for <i><a href="/wiki/Qualit%C3%A4tswein_bestimmter_Anbaugebiete" title="QualitÃ¤tswein bestimmter Anbaugebiete" class="mw-redirect">QualitÃ¤tswein bestimmter Anbaugebiete</a></i>.</dd>
</dl>
<p><a name="QmP" id="QmP"></a></p>
<h5><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Glossary_of_wine_terms&amp;action=edit&amp;section=155" title="Edit section: QmP">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline">QmP</span></h5>
<dl>
<dd>German acronym for <i><a href="/wiki/Qualit%C3%A4tswein_mit_Pr%C3%A4dikat" title="QualitÃ¤tswein mit PrÃ¤dikat" class="mw-redirect">QualitÃ¤tswein mit PrÃ¤dikat</a></i>.</dd>
</dl>
<p><a name="QPR" id="QPR"></a></p>
<h5><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Glossary_of_wine_terms&amp;action=edit&amp;section=156" title="Edit section: QPR">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline">QPR</span></h5>
<dl>
<dd>An acronym for Quality-Price Ratio.</dd>
</dl>
<p><a name="Qualit.C3.A4tswein" id="Qualit.C3.A4tswein"></a></p>
<h5><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Glossary_of_wine_terms&amp;action=edit&amp;section=157" title="Edit section: QualitÃ¤tswein">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline">QualitÃ¤tswein</span></h5>
<dl>
<dd>A designation of better quality <a href="/wiki/German_wine" title="German wine">German wines</a>. When used in isolation on a wine label, it refers to <i>QualitÃ¤tswein bestimmter Anbaugebiete</i>.</dd>
</dl>
<p><a name="Qualit.C3.A4tswein_bestimmter_Anbaugebiete_.28QbA.29" id="Qualit.C3.A4tswein_bestimmter_Anbaugebiete_.28QbA.29"></a></p>
<h5><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Glossary_of_wine_terms&amp;action=edit&amp;section=158" title="Edit section: QualitÃ¤tswein bestimmter Anbaugebiete (QbA)">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline"><a href="/wiki/Qualit%C3%A4tswein_bestimmter_Anbaugebiete" title="QualitÃ¤tswein bestimmter Anbaugebiete" class="mw-redirect">QualitÃ¤tswein bestimmter Anbaugebiete</a> (QbA)</span></h5>
<dl>
<dd>A designation of better quality <a href="/wiki/German_wine" title="German wine">German wines</a> from recognized viticultural areas. It formally represents the second-highest level of German wine.</dd>
</dl>
<p><a name="Qualit.C3.A4tswein_mit_Pr.C3.A4dikat_.28QmP.29" id="Qualit.C3.A4tswein_mit_Pr.C3.A4dikat_.28QmP.29"></a></p>
<h5><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Glossary_of_wine_terms&amp;action=edit&amp;section=159" title="Edit section: QualitÃ¤tswein mit PrÃ¤dikat (QmP)">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline">QualitÃ¤tswein mit PrÃ¤dikat (QmP)</span></h5>
<dl>
<dd>A former designation of the best quality <a href="/wiki/German_wine" title="German wine">German wines</a>, since 2007 shortened to <b><a href="/wiki/Pr%C3%A4dikatswein" title="PrÃ¤dikatswein" class="mw-redirect">PrÃ¤dikatswein</a></b>.</dd>
</dl>
<p><a name="Quality-Price_Ratio_.28QPR.29" id="Quality-Price_Ratio_.28QPR.29"></a></p>
<h5><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Glossary_of_wine_terms&amp;action=edit&amp;section=160" title="Edit section: Quality-Price Ratio (QPR)">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline">Quality-Price Ratio (QPR)</span></h5>
<dl>
<dd>A designation for rating wine based on the ratio of its quality and its price. The higher quality and less expensive price a wine has, the better the ratio.</dd>
</dl>
<p><a name="Quaffing_wine" id="Quaffing_wine"></a></p>
<h5><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Glossary_of_wine_terms&amp;action=edit&amp;section=161" title="Edit section: Quaffing wine">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline"><a href="/wiki/Quaffing" title="Quaffing" class="mw-redirect">Quaffing</a> wine</span></h5>
<dl>
<dd>A simple, everyday drinking wine</dd>
</dl>
<p><a name="Quinta" id="Quinta"></a></p>
<h5><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Glossary_of_wine_terms&amp;action=edit&amp;section=162" title="Edit section: Quinta">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline">Quinta</span></h5>
<dl>
<dd>Portuguese term for a wine estate.</dd>
</dl>
<p><a name="R" id="R"></a></p>
<h2><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Glossary_of_wine_terms&amp;action=edit&amp;section=163" title="Edit section: R">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline">R</span></h2>
<p><a name="Recioto" id="Recioto"></a></p>
<h5><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Glossary_of_wine_terms&amp;action=edit&amp;section=164" title="Edit section: Recioto">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline"><a href="/wiki/Recioto" title="Recioto" class="mw-redirect">Recioto</a></span></h5>
<dl>
<dd>An <a href="/wiki/Italian_(wine)" title="Italian (wine)" class="mw-redirect">Italian</a> <a href="/wiki/Sweet_wine" title="Sweet wine" class="mw-redirect">sweet wine</a> made from <a href="/wiki/Passito" title="Passito" class="mw-redirect">passito</a> grapes.</dd>
</dl>
<p><a name="Redox" id="Redox"></a></p>
<h5><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Glossary_of_wine_terms&amp;action=edit&amp;section=165" title="Edit section: Redox">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline"><a href="/wiki/Redox" title="Redox">Redox</a></span></h5>
<dl>
<dd>A term describing the reductive-<a href="/wiki/Oxidative" title="Oxidative" class="mw-redirect">oxidative</a> way that wine <a href="/wiki/Ages_(wine)" title="Ages (wine)" class="mw-redirect">ages</a>. As one part gains <a href="/wiki/Oxygen" title="Oxygen">oxygen</a> and becomes oxidized, another part loses oxygen and becomes reductive. Early in its life, a wine will exhibit oxidative aromas and traits due to the relatively recent influence and exposure of oxygen when the wine was barrel aged and/or bottled. As the ages and is shut off from a supply of oxygen in the bottle, a mature wine will develop reductive characteristics.</dd>
</dl>
<p><a name="Rehoboam" id="Rehoboam"></a></p>
<h5><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Glossary_of_wine_terms&amp;action=edit&amp;section=166" title="Edit section: Rehoboam">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline"><a href="/wiki/Rehoboam" title="Rehoboam">Rehoboam</a></span></h5>
<dl>
<dd>A large bottle holding 4.5 <a href="/wiki/Litre" title="Litre">litres</a>, the equivalent of six regular <a href="/wiki/Wine_bottle" title="Wine bottle">wine bottles</a>.</dd>
</dl>
<p><a name="Reserva" id="Reserva"></a></p>
<h5><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Glossary_of_wine_terms&amp;action=edit&amp;section=167" title="Edit section: Reserva">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline"><a href="/wiki/Reserva" title="Reserva" class="mw-redirect">Reserva</a></span></h5>
<dl>
<dd>Spanish and Portuguese term for a <a href="/wiki/Reserve_wine" title="Reserve wine">reserve wine</a>.</dd>
</dl>
<p><a name="Reserve" id="Reserve"></a></p>
<h5><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Glossary_of_wine_terms&amp;action=edit&amp;section=168" title="Edit section: Reserve">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline"><a href="/wiki/Reserve_wine" title="Reserve wine">Reserve</a></span></h5>
<dl>
<dd>A term given to wine to indicate that it is of higher quality than usual.</dd>
</dl>
<p><a name="S" id="S"></a></p>
<h2><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Glossary_of_wine_terms&amp;action=edit&amp;section=169" title="Edit section: S">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline">S</span></h2>
<p><a name="Sack" id="Sack"></a></p>
<h5><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Glossary_of_wine_terms&amp;action=edit&amp;section=170" title="Edit section: Sack">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline">Sack</span></h5>
<dl>
<dd>An early English term for what is now called <a href="/wiki/Sherry" title="Sherry">Sherry</a>.</dd>
</dl>
<p><a name="Salmanazar" id="Salmanazar"></a></p>
<h5><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Glossary_of_wine_terms&amp;action=edit&amp;section=171" title="Edit section: Salmanazar">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline"><a href="/wiki/Salmanazar" title="Salmanazar" class="mw-redirect">Salmanazar</a></span></h5>
<dl>
<dd>A large bottle holding nine <a href="/wiki/Litre" title="Litre">litres</a>, the equivalent of 12 regular <a href="/wiki/Wine_bottle" title="Wine bottle">wine bottles</a>.</dd>
</dl>
<p><a name="Sangria" id="Sangria"></a></p>
<h5><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Glossary_of_wine_terms&amp;action=edit&amp;section=172" title="Edit section: Sangria">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline"><a href="/wiki/Sangria" title="Sangria">Sangria</a></span></h5>
<dl>
<dd>A tart <a href="/wiki/Punch_(drink)" title="Punch (drink)">punch</a> made from red wine along with orange, lemon and apricot juice with added sugar.</dd>
</dl>
<p><a name="Sekt" id="Sekt"></a></p>
<h5><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Glossary_of_wine_terms&amp;action=edit&amp;section=173" title="Edit section: Sekt">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline"><a href="/wiki/Sekt" title="Sekt" class="mw-redirect">Sekt</a></span></h5>
<dl>
<dd>A <a href="/wiki/Sparkling_wine" title="Sparkling wine">sparkling wine</a> manufactured in Germany.</dd>
</dl>
<p><a name="Selection_de_grains_nobles" id="Selection_de_grains_nobles"></a></p>
<h5><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Glossary_of_wine_terms&amp;action=edit&amp;section=174" title="Edit section: Selection de grains nobles">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline"><a href="/wiki/Selection_de_grains_nobles" title="Selection de grains nobles" class="mw-redirect">Selection de grains nobles</a></span></h5>
<dl>
<dd>A <a href="/wiki/Sweet_(wine)" title="Sweet (wine)" class="mw-redirect">sweet</a> <a href="/wiki/Botrytized_wine" title="Botrytized wine" class="mw-redirect">botrytized wine</a> made in the <a href="/wiki/French_(wine)" title="French (wine)" class="mw-redirect">French</a> region of <a href="/wiki/Alsace_(wine)" title="Alsace (wine)" class="mw-redirect">Alsace</a></dd>
</dl>
<p><a name="Semi-generic" id="Semi-generic"></a></p>
<h5><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Glossary_of_wine_terms&amp;action=edit&amp;section=175" title="Edit section: Semi-generic">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline"><a href="/wiki/Semi-generic" title="Semi-generic">Semi-generic</a></span></h5>
<dl>
<dd>Wines made in the <a href="/wiki/United_States" title="United States">United States</a> but named after places that the <a href="/wiki/Alcohol_and_Tobacco_Tax_and_Trade_Bureau" title="Alcohol and Tobacco Tax and Trade Bureau">Alcohol and Tobacco Tax and Trade Bureau</a> requires be modified by a US name of geographic origin. Examples would be New York Chablis, Napa Valley Burgundy or California Champagne.</dd>
</dl>
<p><a name="Sherry" id="Sherry"></a></p>
<h5><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Glossary_of_wine_terms&amp;action=edit&amp;section=176" title="Edit section: Sherry">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline"><a href="/wiki/Sherry" title="Sherry">Sherry</a></span></h5>
<dl>
<dd>A <a href="/wiki/Fortified_wine" title="Fortified wine">fortified wine</a> that has been subjected to controlled oxidation to produce a distinctive flavor.</dd>
</dl>
<p><a name="Sommelier" id="Sommelier"></a></p>
<h5><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Glossary_of_wine_terms&amp;action=edit&amp;section=177" title="Edit section: Sommelier">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline"><a href="/wiki/Sommelier" title="Sommelier">Sommelier</a></span></h5>
<dl>
<dd>A wine expert who often works in <a href="/wiki/Restaurant" title="Restaurant">restaurants</a>.</dd>
</dl>
<p><a name="Soutirage" id="Soutirage"></a></p>
<h5><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Glossary_of_wine_terms&amp;action=edit&amp;section=178" title="Edit section: Soutirage">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline">Soutirage</span></h5>
<dl>
<dd>French term for <a href="/wiki/Racking" title="Racking">racking</a>.</dd>
</dl>
<p><a name="Sparkling_wine" id="Sparkling_wine"></a></p>
<h5><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Glossary_of_wine_terms&amp;action=edit&amp;section=179" title="Edit section: Sparkling wine">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline"><a href="/wiki/Sparkling_wine" title="Sparkling wine">Sparkling wine</a></span></h5>
<dl>
<dd><a href="/wiki/Effervescent" title="Effervescent" class="mw-redirect">Effervescent</a> wine containing significant levels of <a href="/wiki/Carbon_dioxide" title="Carbon dioxide">carbon dioxide</a>.</dd>
</dl>
<p><a name="Sp.C3.A4tlese" id="Sp.C3.A4tlese"></a></p>
<h5><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Glossary_of_wine_terms&amp;action=edit&amp;section=180" title="Edit section: SpÃ¤tlese">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline"><a href="/wiki/Sp%C3%A4tlese" title="SpÃ¤tlese">SpÃ¤tlese</a></span></h5>
<dl>
<dd><a href="/wiki/German_language" title="German language">German</a> for "<i><a href="/wiki/Late_harvest_wine" title="Late harvest wine">late harvest</a></i>". A <a href="/wiki/Pr%C3%A4dikat" title="PrÃ¤dikat" class="mw-redirect">PrÃ¤dikat</a> in Germany and Austria.</dd>
</dl>
<p><a name="Split" id="Split"></a></p>
<h5><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Glossary_of_wine_terms&amp;action=edit&amp;section=181" title="Edit section: Split">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline">Split</span></h5>
<dl>
<dd>A wine bottle that holds approximately 6 oz (175-187 mL) or one-fourth the equivalent of a typical 750 mL bottle; a single-serving.</dd>
</dl>
<p><a name="Spritzig" id="Spritzig"></a></p>
<h5><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Glossary_of_wine_terms&amp;action=edit&amp;section=182" title="Edit section: Spritzig">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline">Spritzig</span></h5>
<dl>
<dd>German term for a light sparkling wine.</dd>
</dl>
<p><a name="Spumante" id="Spumante"></a></p>
<h5><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Glossary_of_wine_terms&amp;action=edit&amp;section=183" title="Edit section: Spumante">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline"><a href="/wiki/Spumante" title="Spumante" class="mw-redirect">Spumante</a></span></h5>
<dl>
<dd><a href="/wiki/Italian_language" title="Italian language">Italian</a> for "<i>sparkling</i>".</dd>
</dl>
<p><a name="Stickies" id="Stickies"></a></p>
<h5><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Glossary_of_wine_terms&amp;action=edit&amp;section=184" title="Edit section: Stickies">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline">Stickies</span></h5>
<dl>
<dd>An <a href="/wiki/Australian_(wine)" title="Australian (wine)" class="mw-redirect">Australian</a> term for a broad category of sweet wines included <a href="/wiki/Fortified_(wine)" title="Fortified (wine)" class="mw-redirect">fortified</a> and <a href="/wiki/Botrytized_wines" title="Botrytized wines" class="mw-redirect">botrytized wines</a>.</dd>
</dl>
<p><a name="Strohwein" id="Strohwein"></a></p>
<h5><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Glossary_of_wine_terms&amp;action=edit&amp;section=185" title="Edit section: Strohwein">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline"><a href="/wiki/Strohwein" title="Strohwein" class="mw-redirect">Strohwein</a></span></h5>
<dl>
<dd>A German word for "straw wine", same as the French term <i>vin de paille</i>. Refers to a <a href="/wiki/Dried_grape_wine" title="Dried grape wine" class="mw-redirect">dried grape wine</a>. A <a href="/wiki/Pr%C3%A4dikat" title="PrÃ¤dikat" class="mw-redirect">PrÃ¤dikat</a> in Austria.</dd>
</dl>
<p><a name="Super_Seconds" id="Super_Seconds"></a></p>
<h5><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Glossary_of_wine_terms&amp;action=edit&amp;section=186" title="Edit section: Super Seconds">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline">Super Seconds</span></h5>
<dl>
<dd>A term used in relation to lower classified <a href="/wiki/Bordeaux_wine" title="Bordeaux wine">Bordeaux wine</a> estates that come close in quality to the <a href="/wiki/First_Growth" title="First Growth">First Growth</a> Bordeaux estates.</dd>
</dl>
<p><a name="Super_Tuscans" id="Super_Tuscans"></a></p>
<h5><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Glossary_of_wine_terms&amp;action=edit&amp;section=187" title="Edit section: Super Tuscans">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline"><a href="/wiki/Super_Tuscans" title="Super Tuscans" class="mw-redirect">Super Tuscans</a></span></h5>
<dl>
<dd>A style of <a href="/wiki/Italian_wine" title="Italian wine">Italian wine</a> that became popular in <a href="/wiki/Tuscany_(wine)" title="Tuscany (wine)" class="mw-redirect">Tuscany</a> in the late 20th century where premium quality wines were produced outside of DOC regulations and sold for high prices with the low level <i><a href="/wiki/Vino_da_tavola" title="Vino da tavola" class="mw-redirect">vino da tavola</a></i> designation.</dd>
</dl>
<p><a name="T" id="T"></a></p>
<h2><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Glossary_of_wine_terms&amp;action=edit&amp;section=188" title="Edit section: T">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline">T</span></h2>
<p><a name="Table_wine" id="Table_wine"></a></p>
<h5><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Glossary_of_wine_terms&amp;action=edit&amp;section=189" title="Edit section: Table wine">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline"><a href="/wiki/Table_wine" title="Table wine">Table wine</a></span></h5>
<dl>
<dd>Generally any wine that is not <a href="/wiki/Sparkling_wine" title="Sparkling wine">sparkling</a> or <a href="/wiki/Fortified_wine" title="Fortified wine">fortified</a>. In the US these wines must also be between 7% and 14% alcohol by volume. The term table wine is also used to describe a wine that is considered a good, everyday drinker.</dd>
</dl>
<p><a name="Tafelwein" id="Tafelwein"></a></p>
<h5><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Glossary_of_wine_terms&amp;action=edit&amp;section=190" title="Edit section: Tafelwein">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline"><a href="/wiki/Tafelwein" title="Tafelwein" class="mw-redirect">Tafelwein</a></span></h5>
<dl>
<dd>German term for table wine.</dd>
</dl>
<p><a name="Talento" id="Talento"></a></p>
<h5><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Glossary_of_wine_terms&amp;action=edit&amp;section=191" title="Edit section: Talento">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline">Talento</span></h5>
<dl>
<dd>An <a href="/wiki/Italian_(wine)" title="Italian (wine)" class="mw-redirect">Italian</a> <a href="/wiki/Sparkling_wine" title="Sparkling wine">sparkling wine</a> made according to the <a href="/wiki/Traditional_method" title="Traditional method" class="mw-redirect">traditional method</a> of Champagne--similar to the <a href="/wiki/Spanish_(wine)" title="Spanish (wine)" class="mw-redirect">Spanish</a> term <a href="/wiki/Cava" title="Cava" class="mw-redirect">Cava</a>.</dd>
</dl>
<p><a name="Tastevin" id="Tastevin"></a></p>
<h5><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Glossary_of_wine_terms&amp;action=edit&amp;section=192" title="Edit section: Tastevin">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline"><a href="/wiki/Tastevin" title="Tastevin" class="mw-redirect">Tastevin</a></span></h5>
<dl>
<dd>A silver, shallow cup used for tasting wine.</dd>
</dl>
<p><a name="Tasting_flight" id="Tasting_flight"></a></p>
<h5><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Glossary_of_wine_terms&amp;action=edit&amp;section=193" title="Edit section: Tasting flight">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline"><a href="/wiki/Tasting_flight" title="Tasting flight" class="mw-redirect">Tasting flight</a></span></h5>
<dl>
<dd>Refers to a selection of wines, usually between three and eight glasses, but sometimes as many as fifty, presented for the purpose of sampling and comparison.</dd>
</dl>
<p><a name="T.B.A." id="T.B.A."></a></p>
<h5><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Glossary_of_wine_terms&amp;action=edit&amp;section=194" title="Edit section: T.B.A.">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline">T.B.A.</span></h5>
<dl>
<dd>An abbreviation for the German wine <a href="/wiki/Trockenbeerenauslese" title="Trockenbeerenauslese">Trockenbeerenauslese</a>.</dd>
</dl>
<p><a name="Trocken" id="Trocken"></a></p>
<h5><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Glossary_of_wine_terms&amp;action=edit&amp;section=195" title="Edit section: Trocken">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline">Trocken</span></h5>
<dl>
<dd>German for "<i>dry</i>".</dd>
</dl>
<p><a name="Trockenbeerenauslese" id="Trockenbeerenauslese"></a></p>
<h5><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Glossary_of_wine_terms&amp;action=edit&amp;section=196" title="Edit section: Trockenbeerenauslese">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline"><a href="/wiki/Trockenbeerenauslese" title="Trockenbeerenauslese">Trockenbeerenauslese</a></span></h5>
<dl>
<dd>A German term meaning approximately "harvest of selected dry berries". A type of German wine made from grapes affected by <a href="/wiki/Noble_rot" title="Noble rot">noble rot</a>. Such grapes can be so rare that it can take a skilled picker a day to gather enough for just one bottle.<sup id="cite_ref-MacNeil_pg_523_7-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-MacNeil_pg_523-7" title=""><span>[</span>8<span>]</span></a></sup> A <a href="/wiki/Pr%C3%A4dikat" title="PrÃ¤dikat" class="mw-redirect">PrÃ¤dikat</a> in Germany and Austria.</dd>
</dl>
<p><a name="Typicity" id="Typicity"></a></p>
<h5><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Glossary_of_wine_terms&amp;action=edit&amp;section=197" title="Edit section: Typicity">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline"><a href="/wiki/Typicity" title="Typicity">Typicity</a></span></h5>
<dl>
<dd>A term used to describe how well a wine reflects the characteristics of its <a href="/wiki/Grape_variety" title="Grape variety" class="mw-redirect">grape variety</a> and <i><a href="/wiki/Terroir" title="Terroir">terroir</a></i></dd>
</dl>
<p><a name="U" id="U"></a></p>
<h2><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Glossary_of_wine_terms&amp;action=edit&amp;section=198" title="Edit section: U">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline">U</span></h2>
<p><a name="UC" id="UC"></a></p>
<h5><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Glossary_of_wine_terms&amp;action=edit&amp;section=199" title="Edit section: UC">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline">UC</span></h5>
<dl>
<dd>Abbreviation for the French term <i>Union CoopÃ©rative</i> denoting a regional or local cooperative.</dd>
</dl>
<p><a name="Ullage" id="Ullage"></a></p>
<h5><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Glossary_of_wine_terms&amp;action=edit&amp;section=200" title="Edit section: Ullage">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline"><a href="/wiki/Ullage" title="Ullage">Ullage</a></span></h5>
<dl>
<dd>The space between the wine and the top of a wine bottle. As a wine ages, the space of ullage will increase as the wine gradually evaporates and seeps through the cork. The <a href="/wiki/Winemaking_term" title="Winemaking term" class="mw-redirect">winemaking term</a> of "ullage" refers to the practice of topping off a barrel with extra wine to prevent <a href="/wiki/Oxidation" title="Oxidation" class="mw-redirect">oxidation</a>.</dd>
</dl>
<p><a name="Uvaggio" id="Uvaggio"></a></p>
<h5><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Glossary_of_wine_terms&amp;action=edit&amp;section=201" title="Edit section: Uvaggio">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline">Uvaggio</span></h5>
<dl>
<dd>An Italian term for a wine that has been blended from several <a href="/wiki/Grape_varieties" title="Grape varieties" class="mw-redirect">grape varieties</a>-the opposite of a <a href="/wiki/Varietal" title="Varietal">varietal</a>. An example would be a <a href="/wiki/Chianti" title="Chianti">Chianti</a> that is based on <a href="/wiki/Sangiovese" title="Sangiovese">Sangiovese</a> but include other grape varieties in the bend.</dd>
</dl>
<p><a name="V" id="V"></a></p>
<h2><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Glossary_of_wine_terms&amp;action=edit&amp;section=202" title="Edit section: V">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline">V</span></h2>
<p><a name="Varietal" id="Varietal"></a></p>
<h5><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Glossary_of_wine_terms&amp;action=edit&amp;section=203" title="Edit section: Varietal">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline"><a href="/wiki/Varietal" title="Varietal">Varietal</a></span></h5>
<dl>
<dd>Wines made from a single <a href="/wiki/List_of_grape_varieties" title="List of grape varieties">grape variety</a>.</dd>
</dl>
<p><a name="VC" id="VC"></a></p>
<h5><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Glossary_of_wine_terms&amp;action=edit&amp;section=204" title="Edit section: VC">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline">VC</span></h5>
<dl>
<dd>Abbreviation for the <a href="/wiki/Spanish_(wine)" title="Spanish (wine)" class="mw-redirect">Spanish</a> term <i>vino comarcal</i> denoting a local wine similar to a <i><a href="/wiki/Vin_de_pays" title="Vin de pays">vin de pays</a></i> in <a href="/wiki/France_(wine)" title="France (wine)" class="mw-redirect">France</a>.</dd>
</dl>
<p><a name="VDL" id="VDL"></a></p>
<h5><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Glossary_of_wine_terms&amp;action=edit&amp;section=205" title="Edit section: VDL">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline">VDL</span></h5>
<dl>
<dd>Abbreviation for the French term <i><a href="/wiki/Vin_de_liqueur" title="Vin de liqueur">vin de liqueur</a></i> denoting a wine that has been <a href="/wiki/Fortified_(wine)" title="Fortified (wine)" class="mw-redirect">fortified</a> prior to <a href="/wiki/Fermentation_(wine)" title="Fermentation (wine)">fermentation</a></dd>
</dl>
<p><a name="VDLT" id="VDLT"></a></p>
<h5><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Glossary_of_wine_terms&amp;action=edit&amp;section=206" title="Edit section: VDLT">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline">VDLT</span></h5>
<dl>
<dd>Abbreviation for the Spanish term <i>vino de la tierra</i> denoting a "country wine" similar to the <a href="/wiki/VDQS" title="VDQS" class="mw-redirect">VDQS</a> system of France.</dd>
</dl>
<p><a name="VDN" id="VDN"></a></p>
<h5><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Glossary_of_wine_terms&amp;action=edit&amp;section=207" title="Edit section: VDN">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline">VDN</span></h5>
<dl>
<dd>Abbreviation for the French term <i><a href="/wiki/Vin_doux_naturel" title="Vin doux naturel" class="mw-redirect">vin doux naturel</a></i> denoting a wine that has been fortified during fermentation.</dd>
</dl>
<p><a name="VDQS" id="VDQS"></a></p>
<h5><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Glossary_of_wine_terms&amp;action=edit&amp;section=208" title="Edit section: VDQS">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline"><a href="/wiki/VDQS" title="VDQS" class="mw-redirect">VDQS</a></span></h5>
<dl>
<dd>Abbreviation for the the French <i><a href="/wiki/Vin_D%C3%A9limit%C3%A9_de_Qualit%C3%A9_Sup%C3%A9rieure" title="Vin DÃ©limitÃ© de QualitÃ© SupÃ©rieure">Vin DÃ©limitÃ© de QualitÃ© SupÃ©rieure</a></i> system that ranks below <i><a href="/wiki/Appellation_d%27Origine_Contr%C3%B4l%C3%A9e" title="Appellation d'Origine ContrÃ´lÃ©e" class="mw-redirect">Appellation d'Origine ContrÃ´lÃ©e</a></i> (AOC) but above <i>Vin de pays</i> (country wine).</dd>
</dl>
<p><a name="VDT" id="VDT"></a></p>
<h5><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Glossary_of_wine_terms&amp;action=edit&amp;section=209" title="Edit section: VDT">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline">VDT</span></h5>
<dl>
<dd>Abbreviation for the <a href="/wiki/Italian_(wine)" title="Italian (wine)" class="mw-redirect">Italian</a> term <i><a href="/wiki/Vino_da_tavola" title="Vino da tavola" class="mw-redirect">vino da tavola</a></i> denoting a <a href="/wiki/Table_wine" title="Table wine">table wine</a>.</dd>
</dl>
<p><a name="Vendange_tardive" id="Vendange_tardive"></a></p>
<h5><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Glossary_of_wine_terms&amp;action=edit&amp;section=210" title="Edit section: Vendange tardive">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline">Vendange tardive</span></h5>
<dl>
<dd>French term denoting a <a href="/wiki/Late_harvest_wine" title="Late harvest wine">late harvest wine</a>.</dd>
</dl>
<p><a name="Vermouth" id="Vermouth"></a></p>
<h5><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Glossary_of_wine_terms&amp;action=edit&amp;section=211" title="Edit section: Vermouth">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline"><a href="/wiki/Vermouth" title="Vermouth">Vermouth</a></span></h5>
<dl>
<dd>An <a href="/w/index.php?title=Aromatized_wine&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1" class="new" title="Aromatized wine (page does not exist)">aromatized wine</a> that is made with <a href="/wiki/Wormwood" title="Wormwood">wormwood</a> and potentially other ingredients.</dd>
</dl>
<p><a name="Vertical_and_horizontal_wine_tasting" id="Vertical_and_horizontal_wine_tasting"></a></p>
<h5><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Glossary_of_wine_terms&amp;action=edit&amp;section=212" title="Edit section: Vertical and horizontal wine tasting">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline"><a href="/wiki/Vertical_and_horizontal_wine_tasting" title="Vertical and horizontal wine tasting" class="mw-redirect">Vertical and horizontal wine tasting</a></span></h5>
<dl>
<dd>In a vertical tasting, different vintages of the same wine type from the same winery are tasted. This emphasizes differences between various vintages. In a horizontal tasting, the wines are all from the same vintage but are from different wineries. Keeping wine variety or type and wine region the same helps emphasize differences in winery styles.</dd>
</dl>
<p><a name="Vigneron" id="Vigneron"></a></p>
<h5><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Glossary_of_wine_terms&amp;action=edit&amp;section=213" title="Edit section: Vigneron">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline"><a href="/wiki/Vigneron" title="Vigneron">Vigneron</a></span></h5>
<dl>
<dd><a href="/wiki/French_language" title="French language">French</a> for <i>vine grower</i>.</dd>
</dl>
<p><a name="Vignoble" id="Vignoble"></a></p>
<h5><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Glossary_of_wine_terms&amp;action=edit&amp;section=214" title="Edit section: Vignoble">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline">Vignoble</span></h5>
<dl>
<dd>French term for a "vineyard"</dd>
</dl>
<p><a name="Vin" id="Vin"></a></p>
<h5><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Glossary_of_wine_terms&amp;action=edit&amp;section=215" title="Edit section: Vin">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline"><a href="/wiki/Vin" title="Vin">Vin</a></span></h5>
<dl>
<dd>French for <i>wine</i>.</dd>
</dl>
<p><a name="Vi.C3.B1a" id="Vi.C3.B1a"></a></p>
<h5><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Glossary_of_wine_terms&amp;action=edit&amp;section=216" title="Edit section: ViÃ±a">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline">ViÃ±a</span></h5>
<dl>
<dd><a href="/wiki/Spanish_language" title="Spanish language">Spanish</a> for <i><a href="/wiki/Vines" title="Vines" class="mw-redirect">vines</a></i>.</dd>
</dl>
<p><a name="Vin_de_garde" id="Vin_de_garde"></a></p>
<h5><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Glossary_of_wine_terms&amp;action=edit&amp;section=217" title="Edit section: Vin de garde">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline">Vin de garde</span></h5>
<dl>
<dd>French term for a wine with the potential to improvement with <a href="/wiki/Age_(wine)" title="Age (wine)" class="mw-redirect">age</a>.</dd>
</dl>
<p><a name="Vin_de_glace" id="Vin_de_glace"></a></p>
<h5><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Glossary_of_wine_terms&amp;action=edit&amp;section=218" title="Edit section: Vin de glace">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline">Vin de glace</span></h5>
<dl>
<dd>French term for an <a href="/wiki/Ice_wine" title="Ice wine">ice wine</a>.</dd>
</dl>
<p><a name="Vin_de_pays" id="Vin_de_pays"></a></p>
<h5><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Glossary_of_wine_terms&amp;action=edit&amp;section=219" title="Edit section: Vin de pays">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline"><a href="/wiki/Vin_de_pays" title="Vin de pays">Vin de pays</a></span></h5>
<dl>
<dd>French classification system denoting wines that are above vin de table but below VDQS.</dd>
</dl>
<p><a name="Vin_de_table" id="Vin_de_table"></a></p>
<h5><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Glossary_of_wine_terms&amp;action=edit&amp;section=220" title="Edit section: Vin de table">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline"><a href="/wiki/Vin_de_table" title="Vin de table" class="mw-redirect">Vin de table</a></span></h5>
<dl>
<dd>French term denoting a table wine, the lowest classification of the French AOC system.</dd>
</dl>
<p><a name="Vi.C3.B1edo" id="Vi.C3.B1edo"></a></p>
<h5><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Glossary_of_wine_terms&amp;action=edit&amp;section=221" title="Edit section: ViÃ±edo">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline">ViÃ±edo</span></h5>
<dl>
<dd>Spanish for <i>vineyard</i></dd>
</dl>
<p><a name="Vinho" id="Vinho"></a></p>
<h5><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Glossary_of_wine_terms&amp;action=edit&amp;section=222" title="Edit section: Vinho">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline">Vinho</span></h5>
<dl>
<dd><a href="/wiki/Portuguese_language" title="Portuguese language">Portuguese</a> for <i>wine</i>.</dd>
</dl>
<p><a name="Vinho_regional" id="Vinho_regional"></a></p>
<h5><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Glossary_of_wine_terms&amp;action=edit&amp;section=223" title="Edit section: Vinho regional">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline"><a href="/wiki/Vinho_regional" title="Vinho regional" class="mw-redirect">Vinho regional</a></span></h5>
<dl>
<dd>The lowest level of the <a href="/wiki/Portuguese_(wine)" title="Portuguese (wine)" class="mw-redirect">Portuguese</a> classification system. Similar to a <i>vin de pays</i>.</dd>
</dl>
<p><a name="Vin_mousseux" id="Vin_mousseux"></a></p>
<h5><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Glossary_of_wine_terms&amp;action=edit&amp;section=224" title="Edit section: Vin mousseux">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline">Vin mousseux</span></h5>
<dl>
<dd>Generic French term for a <a href="/wiki/Sparkling_wine" title="Sparkling wine">sparkling wine</a>.</dd>
</dl>
<p><a name="Vin_nouveau" id="Vin_nouveau"></a></p>
<h5><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Glossary_of_wine_terms&amp;action=edit&amp;section=225" title="Edit section: Vin nouveau">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline"><a href="/wiki/Vin_nouveau" title="Vin nouveau" class="mw-redirect">Vin nouveau</a></span></h5>
<dl>
<dd>French term similar to <a href="/wiki/Vin_primeur" title="Vin primeur" class="mw-redirect">Vin primeur</a> denoting a very young wine meant to be consumed within the same <a href="/wiki/Vintage" title="Vintage">vintage</a> year it was produced. Example: <a href="/wiki/Beaujolais_nouveau" title="Beaujolais nouveau">Beaujolais nouveau</a>.</dd>
</dl>
<p><a name="Vin_ordinaire" id="Vin_ordinaire"></a></p>
<h5><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Glossary_of_wine_terms&amp;action=edit&amp;section=226" title="Edit section: Vin ordinaire">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline">Vin ordinaire</span></h5>
<dl>
<dd>French term used to denote an "ordinary wine" as opposed to a premium quality wine.</dd>
</dl>
<p><a name="Vino" id="Vino"></a></p>
<h5><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Glossary_of_wine_terms&amp;action=edit&amp;section=227" title="Edit section: Vino">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline">Vino</span></h5>
<dl>
<dd><a href="/wiki/Italian_language" title="Italian language">Italian</a> and <a href="/wiki/Spanish_language" title="Spanish language">Spanish</a>, Originally derived from <a href="/wiki/Latin" title="Latin">Latin</a>, for <i>wine</i>.</dd>
</dl>
<p><a name="Vino_da_tavola" id="Vino_da_tavola"></a></p>
<h5><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Glossary_of_wine_terms&amp;action=edit&amp;section=228" title="Edit section: Vino da tavola">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline">Vino da tavola</span></h5>
<dl>
<dd>Italian term for "table wine"</dd>
</dl>
<p><a name="Vino_de_mesa" id="Vino_de_mesa"></a></p>
<h5><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Glossary_of_wine_terms&amp;action=edit&amp;section=229" title="Edit section: Vino de mesa">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline">Vino de mesa</span></h5>
<dl>
<dd>Spanish term for "table wine"</dd>
</dl>
<p><a name="Vino_novello" id="Vino_novello"></a></p>
<h5><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Glossary_of_wine_terms&amp;action=edit&amp;section=230" title="Edit section: Vino novello">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline">Vino novello</span></h5>
<dl>
<dd>Italian term for a <i>Vin primeur</i></dd>
</dl>
<p><a name="Vinous" id="Vinous"></a></p>
<h5><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Glossary_of_wine_terms&amp;action=edit&amp;section=231" title="Edit section: Vinous">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline">Vinous</span></h5>
<dl>
<dd>A term used to denoting anything relating to wine.</dd>
</dl>
<p><a name="W" id="W"></a></p>
<h2><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Glossary_of_wine_terms&amp;action=edit&amp;section=232" title="Edit section: W">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline">W</span></h2>
<div class="thumb tright">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:202px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Waiter%27s_Corkscrew.jpg" class="image" title="A waiter's friend type corkscrew"><img alt="" src="http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/d/d7/Waiter%27s_Corkscrew.jpg/200px-Waiter%27s_Corkscrew.jpg" width="200" height="100" border="0" class="thumbimage" /></a>
<div class="thumbcaption">
<div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:Waiter%27s_Corkscrew.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"><img src="/skins-1.5/common/images/magnify-clip.png" width="15" height="11" alt="" /></a></div>
<small>A waiter's friend type corkscrew</small></div>
</div>
</div>
<p><a name="Waiter.27s_friend" id="Waiter.27s_friend"></a></p>
<h5><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Glossary_of_wine_terms&amp;action=edit&amp;section=233" title="Edit section: Waiter's friend">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline">Waiter's friend</span></h5>
<dl>
<dd>A popular type of <a href="/wiki/Corkscrew" title="Corkscrew">corkscrew</a> used commonly in the hospitality industry.</dd>
</dl>
<p><a name="Weissherbst" id="Weissherbst"></a></p>
<h5><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Glossary_of_wine_terms&amp;action=edit&amp;section=234" title="Edit section: Weissherbst">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline">Weissherbst</span></h5>
<dl>
<dd>A <a href="/wiki/German_(wine)" title="German (wine)" class="mw-redirect">German</a> <i><a href="/wiki/Ros%C3%A9" title="RosÃ©">rosÃ©</a></i> made from only black grape varieties such as <a href="/wiki/Pinot_noir" title="Pinot noir">Pinot noir</a>.</dd>
</dl>
<p><a name="Wine" id="Wine"></a></p>
<h5><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Glossary_of_wine_terms&amp;action=edit&amp;section=235" title="Edit section: Wine">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline"><a href="/wiki/Wine" title="Wine">Wine</a></span></h5>
<dl>
<dd>An alcoholic beverage made from the <a href="/wiki/Fermentation_(wine)" title="Fermentation (wine)">fermentation</a> of unmodified <a href="/wiki/Grape" title="Grape">grape</a> juice.</dd>
</dl>
<p><a name="Wine_fraud" id="Wine_fraud"></a></p>
<h5><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Glossary_of_wine_terms&amp;action=edit&amp;section=236" title="Edit section: Wine fraud">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline"><a href="/wiki/Wine_fraud" title="Wine fraud">Wine fraud</a></span></h5>
<dl>
<dd>Any form of dishonesty in the production or distribution of wine.</dd>
</dl>
<p><a name="Wine_label" id="Wine_label"></a></p>
<h5><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Glossary_of_wine_terms&amp;action=edit&amp;section=237" title="Edit section: Wine label">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline"><a href="/wiki/Wine_label" title="Wine label">Wine label</a></span></h5>
<dl>
<dd>The descriptive sticker or signage adhered to the side of a wine bottle.</dd>
</dl>
<p><a name="Wine_lake" id="Wine_lake"></a></p>
<h5><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Glossary_of_wine_terms&amp;action=edit&amp;section=238" title="Edit section: Wine lake">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline"><a href="/wiki/Wine_lake" title="Wine lake">Wine lake</a></span></h5>
<dl>
<dd>Refers to the continuing surplus of wine over demand (glut) being produced in the <a href="/wiki/European_Union" title="European Union">European Union</a>.</dd>
</dl>
<p><a name="Wine_tasting" id="Wine_tasting"></a></p>
<h5><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Glossary_of_wine_terms&amp;action=edit&amp;section=239" title="Edit section: Wine tasting">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline"><a href="/wiki/Wine_tasting" title="Wine tasting">Wine tasting</a></span></h5>
<dl>
<dd>The sensory evaluation of wine, encompassing more than taste, but also mouthfeel, aroma, and colour.</dd>
</dl>
<p><a name="Y" id="Y"></a></p>
<h2><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Glossary_of_wine_terms&amp;action=edit&amp;section=240" title="Edit section: Y">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline">Y</span></h2>
<p><a name="Z" id="Z"></a></p>
<h2><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Glossary_of_wine_terms&amp;action=edit&amp;section=241" title="Edit section: Z">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline">Z</span></h2>
<p><a name="See_also" id="See_also"></a></p>
